{"title_page": "Horrible Histories (2009 TV series)", "text_new": "{{About|the original series|the 2015 revival|Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n\n| image                    = HHlive-actionlogo.png\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = Title logo (with background used from Series 2 - 5)\n| genre                    = Musical<br>Comedy<br>Sketch comedy\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = ''[[Horrible Histories (book series)|Horrible Histories]]''<br>by [[Terry Deary]]<br>[[Peter Hepplewhite]]<br>Neil Tonge\n| developer                = [[Dominic Brigstocke]]<br>Caroline Norris\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Steve Connelly\n* [[Dominic Brigstocke]] (Series 2 to 4)\n* Chloe Thomas (Series 1 and 4)\n}}\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mathew Baynton]]\n* [[Simon Farnaby]]\n* [[Sarah Hadland]]\n* [[Martha Howe-Douglas]]\n* [[Jim Howick]]\n* [[Lawry Lewin]]\n* [[Alice Lowe]]\n* [[Laurence Rickard]]\n* [[Ben Willbond]]\n}}\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = [[John Eccleston]] (Rattus Rattus)<br />[[Jon Culshaw]]<br />[[Jess Robinson]]<br />[[Dave Lamb]]\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = [[Richie Webb]]<br>Matt Katz\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = Richie Webb\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 5\n| num_series               = 8\n| num_episodes             = 105 regular episodes, 10 full-length specials\n| list_episodes            = List of Horrible Histories episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Richard Bradley\n* [[Kim Shillinglaw]] (Series 1)\n* Alison Gregory (Series 2 to 4)\n* Melissa Hardinge (Series 4 and 5)\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Caroline Norris\n* Giles Pilbrow\n* Dominic Brigstocke (Series 1)\n* Imogen Cooper (Series 3 and 4)\n}}\n| editor                   = \n| cinematography           = Peter Edwards\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 28 minutes\n| company                  = Lion TV<br />Citrus Television (Series 2 onwards)\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[CBBC]]<br />[[CBBC HD]]\n| network                  = \n| picture_format           = [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = 16 April 2009\n| last_aired               = 4 August 2014\n| followed_by              = ''[[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|Horrible Histories Specials]]''\n| related                  = ''[[Horrible Histories: Gory Games]]''<br />''[[Horrible Histories with Stephen Fry]]''\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbbc/shows/horrible-histories\n| production_website       = http://www.liontv.com/London/Productions/Horrible-Histories\n}}\n'''''Horrible Histories''''' is a British children's live-action [[historical]] and [[Musical film|musical]] [[sketch comedy]] television series, based on the [[Horrible Histories (book series)|bestselling books of the same name]] by [[Terry Deary]]. The show was produced for [[CBBC]] by [[Lion Television]] with Citrus Television and ran from 2009 to 2013 for five series of thirteen half-hour episodes, with additional one-off seasonal and Olympic specials.\n\nThe TV show carries over the graphic style and much of the content of the [[Horrible Histories (book series)|''Horrible Histories'' book series]]. It maintains the franchise's overall irreverent but accurate focus on the dark, gruesome or scatological aspects of British and other [[Western world]] history, spanning from the [[Stone Age]] to the post-[[World War II]] era. Individual historical eras or civilisations are defined and named as in the books, with sketches from several different time periods combined within a single episode. [[Live-action]] sketches\u2014which often parody other UK media or celebrities\u2014and music videos are intercut with animations and quizzes. The starring troupe are [[Mathew Baynton]], [[Simon Farnaby]], [[Martha Howe-Douglas]], [[Jim Howick]], [[Laurence Rickard]], [[Sarah Hadland]] and [[Ben Willbond]], alongside a large supporting cast headed by [[Katy Wix]], [[Lawry Lewin]], [[Alice Lowe]] and [[Dominique Moore]]. The black rat puppet \"host\", Rattus Rattus, appears in short bridging segments, explaining the factual basis for each sketch.\n\nThe [[Horrible Histories troupe|creative team]] was largely recruited from the mainstream adult UK comedy scene. They took inspiration from such quintessentially British historical-comedy classics as ''[[Blackadder]]'' and the [[Monty Python]] films. The series was a critical and ratings success, eventually gaining a wide all ages audience through its non-condescending and inclusive approach. It has won numerous domestic and international awards and has been named among the greatest British children's television series of all time.\n\nIn 2011, a spin-off game show, ''[[Horrible Histories: Gory Games]]'', was launched on CBBC. In the same year, the original show was repackaged for main channel [[BBC One]] as ''[[Horrible Histories with Stephen Fry]]'', with [[Stephen Fry|Fry]] replacing the puppet, Rattus Rattus, as presenter. [[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|A new series of special episodes]] began airing in 2015, featuring a new format and cast. Although the original series has ended, it continues to be frequently repeated on the [[CBBC Channel]] daily.\n\n==Background==\n''Horrible Histories'' is based on [[Horrible Histories (book series)|the British children's historical-comedy book series]] by [[Terry Deary]], first published by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic UK]] in 1993 and since expanded into a [[Horrible Histories|multimedia franchise]]. The books and subsequent spin-off materials are intended to pique young children's interest in history via short, factually based but humorously told anecdotes highlighting aspects of the subject not usually covered in more traditional educational sources.<ref name=\"scanlon\">{{cite journal | title=History beyond the academy: humor and horror in children's history books | journal=New Review of Children's Literature and Librarianship, 16:2, 69\u201391|volume = 16| issue=2| pages=69\u201391|year=2011| author=Scanlon, Margaret| doi=10.1080/13614541.2010.540197 }}</ref>\n\nLionTV executive producer Richard Bradley, whose company had previously produced several adult history-themed programmes and whose son was a fan of the ''Horrible Histories'' books, was the initial driving force behind a new TV adaptation.<ref name=\"guardian_a\">{{cite web|author=Hickman, Leo |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/mar/17/horrible-histories-huge-hit |title=How Horrible Histories became a huge hit|work=The Guardian |date=17 March 2011|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Deary was initially sceptical, having had a negative experience with the [[Horrible Histories (2001 TV series)|2001 animated series]], which had only loosely incorporated his concept. He finally agreed to the new project on the condition that it be explicitly \"horrible, funny and true\". While disclaiming any active role in developing the subsequent series, he would eventually contribute to the writing as well as appearing in several small roles.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\n\nThe producers were determined that the show be respectful of audience expectations for the Horrible Histories brand, maintaining its familiar visual style and content as far as possible. Early concepts for bringing it to the screen involved framing or interpretive devices, including a ghostly train carrying children into the past, or a wizard storyteller to act as their guide. Eventually Bradley with producer/director [[Dominic Brigstocke]] concluded that the material was strong enough to stand on its own, so they developed, in consultation with CBBC executives, a live-action sketch-comedy showcase.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Once the writing was underway, the producers further discovered that sticking as closely as possible to the historical truth made it easier for them to find the humour within it. They then introduced a comedy style relying on parodies of familiar modern media [[Convention (norm)|conventions]] as a means of making these historical details more immediately accessible.<ref name=\"bcg_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/about/ | title=About: Horrible Histories | work=[[British Comedy Guide]] | accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nTo do the material full justice, Brigstocke and series producer Caroline Norris used their industry contacts to put together a creative team consisting mostly of veterans of the adult UK comedy community.<ref name=\"bcg_a\" /><ref name=\"telegraph_a\"/> The BBC readily agreed to this cross-demographic experiment. They also approved the adoption\u2014insofar as was possible in a programme aimed at young children\u2014of the core franchise precept of \"history with the nasty bits left in\",<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9857326/Horrible-Histories-20-years-of-entertaining-children.html | title=Horrible Histories: 20 years of entertaining children |work=The Daily Telegraph | date=21 February 2013 | accessdate=10 December 2013| author=Preston, Richard}}</ref> which frequently involved \"[[Gross out|gross-out]]\"-style bodily function humour and comic violence.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"telegraph_a\"/>\n\nThe new creative team, while avoiding references aimed specifically at adults, was determined not to adapt the humour to children or otherwise patronise their audience. Instead, they sought to make the best use possible of the material.<ref name=\"express_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/249426/Horrible-Histories-A-funny-way-to-learn | title=Horrible Histories: a funny way to learn |work=[[The Daily Express|The Sunday Express]] |date=29 May 2011| accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Stephenson, David}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcint\">{{cite AV media| title=Interview with Laurence Rickard and Mathew Baynton|work=[[BBC News]] | date=2 June 2010 <!--| accessdate=18 December 2013 No longer available on the BBC website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odo42C6mf4U-->}}</ref> Norris said that her goal was \"to make a show that people would say was too good for children&nbsp;... we started out with really high ambitions.\"<ref name=\"bfi4\"/> To that end, adult historical satires such as ''[[Blackadder]]'' and the [[Monty Python]] films were shown at the first writers' meeting to demonstrate the proposed tone, and these influences would be visible throughout the show's run.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"telegraph_a\">{{cite news|title=How Horrible Histories grew up to be a hit comedy show |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/7765195/How-Horrible-Histories-grew-up-to-be-a-hit-comedy-show.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=17 July 2010|date=25 May 2010|author=West, Naomi}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcint\" /><ref name=\"radiotimes\">{{cite web|author=McLean, Gareth|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-04-09/why-did-the-league-of-gentlemen-choose-to-reform-on-horrible-histories |title=Why did the League of Gentlemen choose to reform on Horrible Histories? |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=9 April 2012|accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\nOnce the first series had aired and it was realised that the overall approach was working well, the creative team built on and significantly expanded the scope of the comedy elements for the second.<ref name=\"bcg_a\"/><ref name=\"express_a\" /> This trend continued through each subsequent series. The net result was a show that immediately appealed to young children while also gaining the increasing respect\u2014and viewership\u2014of older audiences.<ref name=\"bcgpress\">{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/press/ | title='Horrible Histories' in the press |work=British Comedy Guide| accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{Main|List of Horrible Histories (2009 TV series) episodes|l1=List of Horrible Histories episodes}}\n\nThe divisions by historical era or civilisation in the book series are carried over in the TV show, focusing on events in or directly affecting [[Great Britain]] and (to a lesser extent) the larger [[Western world]]. The [[Incan Empire|Inca]] and [[Aztec]] empires are also featured in later series.<ref name=\"popm_a\"/> Sketches are grouped under these divisions, named as in the books, beginning with the Savage [[Stone Age]] and including among others the Cut-throat [[Celts]], Awful [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptians]], Groovy [[Ancient Greece|Greeks]], Rotten [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], Vicious [[Vikings]], Measly [[Middle Ages]], Terrible [[Tudor period|Tudors]], Slimy [[Stuart period|Stuarts]], Gorgeous [[Georgian era|Georgians]] and Vile [[Victorians]]. The timeline for the most part ended at the Woeful Second World War.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"comedy\"/> During the fifth and final series the show featured a handful of significant post-World War II (or \"Troublesome Twentieth Century\") events, including the civil rights movement and the [[Space Race]] between the US and the USSR. The most recent event referenced was the 1969 [[Apollo 11|Apollo 11 Moon landing]].<ref name=\"bfi5\" />\n\n[[File:Horrible Histories animated title cards.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Typical examples of the title cards with animated characters, based on the art style of the books, that introduced sketches]]\n\nEach named division has its own title card that appears before each sketch (or group of sketches) set in that era or civilisation, along with a short introductory animation featuring a period-appropriate character. Throughout each sketch, small pop-up signs are used to affirm the truth (or otherwise) of any particularly implausible-seeming concepts mentioned onscreen.<ref name=\"popm_a\"/> The live-action material is intercut with short animated sketches, quizzes and interludes with puppet \"host\" Rattus Rattus (performed by [[John Eccleston]]), who addresses the viewer directly as a presenter, commenting on and clarifying the factual basis behind the humour. Rattus also occasionally holds up pop-up signs himself during sketches.<ref name=\"comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/ |title=Horrible Histories|work=British Comedy Guide|date= |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/horrible-histories | title=Review: Horrible Histories | work=[[Common Sense Media]]| accessdate=3 March 2014 | author=Ashby, Emily| date=2014-02-28 }}</ref>\n\nSketches were filmed ''en masse'' and then cut into episodes by the producers based on creative rather than chronological or other educational considerations, in the manner of a more traditional sketch-comedy series.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /><ref name=\"FULLSESSION\"/> They often fall under a recurring banner\u2014usually with its own short title sequence\u2014but otherwise vary widely in length, visual style and approach. Many are recognisable parodies of other popular media or celebrities, in formats ranging from spoof commercials to mock TV shows, newscasts, magazines, video games and film trailers.<ref name=\"bcg_a\"/> Notable parody inspirations included ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|Masterchef]]'', ''[[Wife Swap (UK TV series)|Wife Swap]]'', ''[[Come Dine with Me]]'' and ''[[The Apprentice (TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\"/><ref name=\"guardreview\"/> \"Horrible Histories Movie Pitch\", in which historical figures pitch their life stories to a panel of Hollywood producers played by ''[[The League of Gentlemen|League of Gentlemen]]'' actors [[Mark Gatiss]], [[Steve Pemberton]] and [[Reece Shearsmith]], used the format of a former commercial campaign for [[Orange (UK)#Orange Gold Spots|Orange's cinema reminders to turn mobiles off]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/horrible-histories-cbbc-meets-royston-vasey-7621912.html | title=CBBC meets Royston Vasey | work=[[The Independent]] | date=6 August 2012 | accessdate=16 February 2014 | author=Kelly, Stephen}}</ref>\n\nThe show also created several popular recurring characters and concepts, notably \"Stupid Deaths\", in which a skeletal, platinum-blond [[Grim Reaper]] amuses himself while processing souls for admittance to the afterlife by forcing candidates from throughout history to relate the embarrassing details of their demise.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"guardian3_a\" /> HHTV News' Bob Hale and his eccentric-but-erudite in-studio reports provide a broader picture on historical events (such as the [[Wars of the Roses]] and the [[French Revolution]]), in a style reminiscent of presenter [[Peter Snow]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/home/digital-editions/broadcast-hot-100-2012/5056710.article | title=The Horrible Histories team | publisher=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]| work=Broadcast Hot 100 2012 supplement| date=23 May 2013 | accessdate=17 February 2014 | author=Parker, Robin, ed. | pages=17}}</ref><ref name=\"djsketches\">{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/broadcasters/horrible-histories-jubilee-sketches-will-never-be-aired/5043199.article|title=''Horrible Histories'' Jubilee sketches will never be aired|work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|author=Parker, Robin| date=11 June 2012|accessdate=17 February 2014|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The \"Shouty Man\", a parody of a typically ebullient [[infomercial]] host (like [[Neil Burgess (actor)|Barry Scott]]), pitches unusual historical products.<ref name=\"bcg_a\"/>\n\n===Music===\nOriginal music plays a significant role in the show and its popularity; \"Music from ''Horrible Histories''\" was chosen as the [[Horrible Histories Prom|2011 theme]] of the [[The Proms|BBC Proms]]' annual children's concert.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|author=Brogan, Benedict|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/proms/8674648/BBC-Prom-2011-Prom-20-Horrible-histories-Albert-Hall-review.html |title=BBC Prom 2011: Prom 20: Horrible Histories, Albert Hall, review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 August 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref> Alongside various short intro themes and commercial jingles, each episode{{refn|With the exception of Episode 5 of Series 1, produced before the music became a priority as described below.|group=note}} and each special contains at least one longer comedy song centred around a particular historical figure or theme and performed by the cast in appropriate character.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" />\n\nIn the first series, the songs generally had no particular satirical slant, and were often intercut with sketches from the same era. However, after the creative team noted the critical and popular success of the major exception (\"Born 2 Rule\", which featured [[House of Hanover|King Georges I\u2013IV]] performing in the style of a [[boyband]]) the decision was taken from the second series onwards to continue in that vein.<ref name=\"express_a\" /> Historical concepts were matched to a diverse range of modern musical references, and the results were showcased as self-contained music video parodies. The thirteenth episode of the second and each subsequent series was retooled as a \"Savage Songs\" special, featuring a compilation of that series' outstanding videos.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/episodes/ | title=Horrible Histories: Episode Guide| work=British Comedy Guide | accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe songs have since become among the most critically and popularly acclaimed elements of the show, especially among its adult audience. Commentators cite the apt cleverness of the various historical/musical parody match-ups, and the complexity and skill with which the musical elements are executed.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" /><ref name=\"telegraph\" /><ref name=\"radiotimes1\">{{cite web|author=Seale, Jack|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-06-06/horrible-histories-5-brilliant-songs-from-series-5 |title=Horrible Histories: Five brilliant songs from Series 5|work=[[Radio Times]] |date=6 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Principal composer [[Richie Webb]] confirms that the songs became more sophisticated as a result of the show's increasing popularity with older viewers, as well as the demands of increased visibility online.<ref name=\"radiotimes1\" /> Many of the videos have earned standalone popularity on YouTube.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" />\n\nThe videos tend to run about three minutes, with two significant exceptions. \"The English Kings and Queens\", from the third series, lists all of the [[British monarchs]] since [[William the Conqueror]], using a [[Chas & Dave]]-inspired [[cumulative song|cumulative]] format.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" />{{refn|Listen to an audio clip (uploaded by the composer) [https://soundcloud.com/richiewebb/horrible-histories-kings-and here]|group=note}} The creative team wrote the song to challenge the show's young audience, after noting that the same youngsters had been inspired to memorise lyrics to previous songs.<ref name=\"thism_a\">{{cite AV media| title=Interview with Mathew Baynton, Jim Howick and Martha Howe-Douglas| work=[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]| date=12 April 2012 <!-- | accessdate=10 December 2013 No longer available on the programme's website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ShFdlYrw54w-->}}</ref> \"We're History\", styled as a grand finale for the show's final episode, uses stock footage from across the show's run to revisit every major era it ever featured in turn.{{refn|See video clip [http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/videos/5770/ here]|group=note}}\n\n\n==Content and educational value==\nNo formal educational method was applied to the production, and no attempt was made to follow the official [[UK National Curriculum]] for primary school history.<ref name=\"histex_a\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-in-england-history-programmes-of-study | title=National curriculum in England: history programmes of study |work=Official United Kingdom government website | date=11 September 2013 | accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> The show's creators were acutely aware of educational possibilities, but\u2014in line with Deary's overall mandate for the franchise\u2014saw their basic role as popularising history, inspiring further curiosity about the academic subject rather than attempting to teach it seriously.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.timeout.com/london/tv-reviews/yonderland-horribly-ever-after | title=Yonderland: Horribly ever after | work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|date=6 November 2013|accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Tate, Gabriel}}</ref><ref name=\"tbivision_a\">{{cite web | url=http://tbivision.com/highlight/2013/11/kids-tv-seriously/185741/ | title=Kids TV, seriously | work=Television Business International | date=22 November 2013 | accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> The show's effectiveness in this respect was endorsed by historical scholars, including presenter [[Dan Snow]].<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Writing in ''[[The Independent]]'', Gerard Gilbert notes that ''Horrible Histories'' is part of an extensive British [[Black comedy|black-comedy]] tradition not only in adult but also in children's programming.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/horrible-histories-the-best-laughs-are-on-childrens-tv-2194280.html?action=Email |title=Horrible Histories: The best laughs are on children's TV |work=The Independent |date=26 January 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2013|author=Gilbert, Gerard}}</ref> In later series, as usable material from the books began to run out, there was a progression towards more sophisticated, adult sketches in terms of both creativity and educational content, as the show began relying on material that their younger viewers would be less familiar with.<ref name=\"histex_a\"/>\n\n{{quote box|quote=\"My aim for this was always that kids would go away and read up more about a subject. They love all the slapstick, but they also love what Terry does really well in the books\u2014telling you something your parents don\u2019t know. When you\u2019re eight years old you get told what to do by everyone, so being able to teach your dad something is amazing.\"|source=\u2014Caroline Norris, 2013<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\"/>|align=right|width=25em}}\n\nThroughout, emphasis was placed on meshing comedy with the demands of historical accuracy, as defined by the mainstream scholarly consensus on the topic. This stance sometimes encompassed traditionally accepted if not actually well-documented anecdotes, such as those involving [[Caligula]].<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /><ref name=\"histex_a\" /> All the material used on the show was vetted by production assistant and self-described \"tyrannical pedant\" Greg Jenner during both writing and filming; he says that he has counted only eight errors out of more than 4,000 facts presented over the course of the show's run.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /> Costuming and makeup were likewise painstakingly recreated based on primary historical sources where available.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /><ref name=\"bfi5\"/>\n\nWhen an error was discovered, the effort was made to correct it whenever possible. This process is perhaps most noticeable in the evolution of a song featuring the four [[House of Hanover|Hanoverian]] King Georges: lyrics in the original 2009 video incorrectly saying that [[George I of Great Britain|George I]] had \"died on the [[Close stool|loo]]\" were correctly reassigned to [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] for the song's reprise at the show's 2011 BBC Prom concert.<ref name=\"histex_a\" />\n\nTaking cues from what Deary describes as his \"seriously subversive\" attitude towards the mainstream British history education model<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /> meant that the show inevitably incorporated sociopolitical comment. Perhaps most explicitly, Scots-Jamaican nurse [[Mary Seacole]] was deliberately championed in both a sketch and later song as a forgotten heroine in the shadow of [[Florence Nightingale]]. The activities of African-American activists [[Harriet Tubman]] and [[Rosa Parks]] were also showcased, as was ex-slave boxer [[Bill Richmond]].<ref name=\"histex_a\" /> According to Norris, a desire to include more women's stories was hampered by the traditionally male-dominated viewpoint of historical records.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\" /> The show did make an attempt to counteract this by giving showcase songs to the British [[Women's suffrage in the United Kingdom|women's suffrage]] movement and [[Home front during World War II#Mobilisation of women|women's work on the British homefront during World War II]], and wherever possible highlighting strong-willed, dynamic female figures, including [[Queen Victoria]], [[Elizabeth I]] and [[Boudicca]]. Religious controversies, class divisions, the ethics of conquest, and labour conditions were likewise touched on.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\n\nThe association with a proven and popular children's brand focusing on potentially sensitive subjects enabled the TV series to deflect any serious controversy regarding the same subjects, as they had demonstrably already been presented to children without any ill effects.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /> Senior writer [[Steve Punt]] said that there were in fact very few complaints regarding the initial series' content, adding that \"everyone was very relieved\".<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /> The producers did consider some topics intrinsically unsuited for an irreverent comic treatment, as for instance the [[Holocaust]] or the harsher details of slavery, and avoided them accordingly.<ref name=\"express_a\" /><ref name=\"histex_a\" /> Norris has described her personal criteria for age suitability as whether she would be nervous watching it with a ten-year-old.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /> While BBC executives in large part were willing to concede the requirements of reflecting historical realities, some topics, notably suicide, needed careful handling to avoid potentially negative impact on younger viewers.<ref name=\"histex_a\" /> The show sometimes acknowledged particularly emotive subject matter (the World War I [[Christmas truce]], for example) by following up the sketch not with a joke, but a more sombre elaboration of the less comedic details.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\"/>\n\n==Production==\nThe TV series used the [[Horrible Histories]] brand, logo and associated trademarks under licence from publisher [[Scholastic Books]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Loveday, Samantha|url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/horrible-histories-heading-to-tv/038035|title=Horrible Histories heading to TV|work=Licensing.biz|date=11 October 2007|accessdate=8 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112185858/http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/horrible-histories-heading-to-tv/038035|archive-date=12 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was produced for the BBC by LionTV and Citrus Television,{{refn|[http://citrustelevision.com/ Citrus Television] was formed by several of the ''Horrible Histories'' producers during the show's first series, and is credited alongside LionTV from the second series onward.|group=note}} with post-production being handled by Platform Post Production. Under series producer Norris and directors Brigstocke, Steve Connelly and Chloe Thomas, each series of thirteen episodes took approximately one year to produce. The process included several months of research into the historical facts, two to three months of writing, eight weeks of filming both on location and at London's [[Twickenham Studios]], and three to four months of post-production.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fN5AjcqvPvA | title=Symposium: Horrible Histories: A Masterclass|author1=Norris, Caroline |author2=Farnaby, Simon |author3=Howe-Douglas, Martha | publisher=[[Edinburgh International Television Festival|MediaGuardian Edinburgh Television Festival]] 2012 |medium=YouTube|date=19 September 2012 | accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"express2_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/315797/Horrible-History-s-a-hoot | title=Horrible history's a hoot | work=[[The Daily Express]]| date=22 April 2012 | accessdate=11 December 2013|author=Stephenson, David }}</ref>\n\nAt first the sketches were derived almost exclusively from the books, whose multimedia approach, consisting of short anecdotes interspersed with cartoons, diaries, newspaper articles and recipes, proved easily adaptable to the screen either as raw material or creative inspiration.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> In later series, as usable material from the books and other obvious sources began to run out, concepts were drawn from more standard historical texts under Jenner's supervision. He and fellow researchers read through many different studies and picked out suitably quirky, intriguing snippets, which were then pitched to the writers for development.<ref name=\"histex_a\">{{cite web | url=http://d2j7noxmrt3xhh.cloudfront.net/bbchistory/audio/HistoryExtra_2013_05_30.mp3 | title=Podcast: Behind the scenes at Horrible Histories| work=[[BBC History (magazine)|BBC History]] |medium=mp3 podcast file|date=30 May 2013 | accessdate=12 December 2013|author=Hodgman, Charlotte }}</ref>\n\nInspiration for the music videos came from many different sources, and input from all members of the show's creative team was encouraged.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\"/><ref name=\"radiotimes1\"/> With the exception of \"A Gorgeous Georgian Lady\", adapted by Deary from his book ''Gorgeous Georgians'', all songs were original to the series. Once Jenner and Norris had finalised the subject matter and music genre, lyrics were commissioned from the writing team, usually [[Dave Cohen (writer)|Dave Cohen]]. These were rewritten as needed under Norris' supervision to ensure as much factual information as possible was included.<ref name=\"radiotimes1\"/> Webb then composed and recorded each song's instrumental track at Noisegate Studios, hewing as closely as possible to the style of the genre or artist in question. The finished vocal and backing tracks were later returned to Noisegate for post-production by Webb and colleague Matt Katz.<ref name=\"songwriting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/what-s-on/art-of-horrible-songwriting-1-5801893 |title=Art of Horrible songwriting|work=[[Sheffield Telegraph]] |date=28 June 2013 |accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ngmedia\">{{cite web | url=http://www.noisegatemedia.com/portfolio/horrible-histories | title=Noisegate Media Portfolio: Horrible Histories | work=Noisegate Media| accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe 2D animated sequences were directed by Tim Searle of Baby Cow Animation, based on [[Martin Brown (artist)|Martin Brown]]'s illustrations for the books.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.babycow.tv/ | title=Baby Cow Animation: Design & Production | work=Baby Cow Animation | accessdate=27 February 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226215952/http://www.babycow.tv/ | archivedate=26 February 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"youtube_a\">{{cite AV media |title=Horrible Histories behind the scenes: find out how we make the drawings come alive |publisher=CBBC Online|work=Horrible Histories: Behind the Scenes<!--|accessdate=7 February 2014 Part of a video extra series released on the CBBC website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oQFHA_s9yIg -->}}</ref> They were voiced by [[Jon Culshaw]] and [[Jess Robinson]] along with various regular cast members. Video game-styled sketches were achieved using a mix of [[3D computer graphics|3D]] animation and live-action [[green-screen]] footage.<ref>{{cite AV media |title=Horrible Histories behind the scenes: special effects with just a big green sheet|publisher=CBBC Online|work=Horrible Histories: Behind the Scenes<!--|accessdate=27 February 2014 Part of a video extra series released on the CBBC website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2MDDvdl1SX8-->}}</ref> Properties frequently were modified foodstuffs, with melted chocolate bars standing in for excrement and soup for vomit.<ref name=\"bfi4\"/>\n\nEach series debuted in the UK in April or May from 2009 to 2013, and on international channels including Canada's [[BBC Kids]], Malaysia's [[NTV7]], The Philippines [[GMA Network]], and Australia's [[ABC3]]. Six special episodes, comprising a mix of new and existing material around a single theme, were broadcast in the UK. \"Horrible Christmas\" (aired in 2010) was followed by a \"Sport Special\" (July 2012, to coincide with the [[2012 London Olympic Games]]) and a \"Scary Special\" (autumn 2012, themed around [[Halloween]]). \"Ridiculous Romance\" (themed around [[Valentine's Day]]) aired in February 2014; the \"Frightful First World War Special\" aired later the same year, as part of the BBC's commemoration of the 100th anniversary of the outbreak of [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/episodes/2014/1/ | title=2014 Specials \u2013 Horrible Histories | work=British Comedy Guide | date=23 January 2014 | accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BCAspecials\" />\n\nIn autumn 2011, the BBC edited footage from the show's [[Horrible Histories Prom|summer Prom concert]] into an hour-long TV special (\"Horrible Histories' Big Prom Party\"), featuring specially shot linking sketches.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b014b89k | title=CBBC Proms: Horrible Histories' Big Prom Party | work=BBC Proms online guide | accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> In addition, standalone sketches hosted by [[Stephen Fry]], as well as a special \"Bob Hale Report\", were produced as part of the 2012 [[Sport Relief]] benefit programme.<ref name=\"sprelief\">{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories_stephen_fry/episodes/1/7/ | title=Horrible Histories With Stephen Fry: Sport Relief Special | work=British Comedy Guide | date=23 March 2012 | accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/pxgst/horrible-histories--horrible-histories-sport-relief-bob-report | title=Horrible Histories Sport Relief: The Bob Report | work=[[Radio Times]] | date=20 August 2012 | accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> In the same year, several sketches were commissioned as part of the BBC's live television coverage of the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]], to be performed on [[Tower Bridge]], but due to time constraints only one was aired.<ref name=\"djsketches\"/>\n\nThe  producers decided to cease full-time production after the fifth series, citing concerns around the increasing difficulty in finding suitable historical material.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/402593/The-end-of-history-as-we-know-it | title=The end of history as we know it | work=[[The Daily Express|The Sunday Express]]| date=26 May 2013 | accessdate=26 December 2013 | author=Stephenson, David}}</ref> However, the possibility of further specials marking important historical or holiday milestones has been discussed.<ref name=\"BCAspecials\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/000001192/ |title=Horrible Histories to continue with specials|work=British Comedy Guide|date=5 July 2013 |accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the BBC announced that the ''Horrible Histories'' concept would be revived in a new format, focussing on the life and times of a single historical figure per episode. The [[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|rebooted series]] was again developed by LionTV and will involve a largely all-new production team and cast, while still retaining Jenner as lead historical consultant and many of the original series's writers. In addition, original stars Farnaby and Howick will return in limited roles.<ref name=\"Series6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/horrible-histories |title=Top comedy stars join CBBC's Horrible Histories|work=BBC Media Centre|date=5 January 2015 |accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\nThe cast members were recruited from sketch and character comedy, having previously had roles in ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'', ''[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]'', ''[[The Thick of It]]'' and ''[[The Mighty Boosh (TV series)|The Mighty Boosh]]'' TV series among others. Several of the writers and researchers also occasionally appeared in front of the camera, including Punt, Jenner, George Sawyer and Susie Donkin, while actors [[Mathew Baynton]] and [[Ben Willbond]] sometimes contributed to the writing. [[Laurence Rickard]] was recruited solely as a writer, but found himself part of both the senior writing staff and starring cast after creating the character of Bob Hale, whose extended, convoluted monologues proved impossible to hand over to anyone else.<ref name=\"bfi4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/live/video/920 |title=Horrible Histories Series Four BFI Q&A |publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=19 June 2013|author=Norris, Caroline with the starring cast}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The starring cast of TV series Horrible Histories arrives at the Children's BAFTAs, 27 November 2011.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The starring cast at the 2011 Children's BAFTAs. L-R: Simon Farnaby, Martha Howe-Douglas, Mathew Baynton, Laurence Rickard, Ben Willbond and Jim Howick]]\n\nIndividual sketches and songs were cast by the production team, sometimes acting on input from the show's stable of performers themselves. While certain roles naturally lent themselves to a particular actor, Norris said that confidence in the entire cast's ability was such that the producers also experimented with casting against type.<ref name=\"bfi4\"/> The demands of filming thirteen episodes' worth of material in the same timeframe as a standard six-episode sketch show, while coping with the many complex makeup and wardrobe changes required, resulted in casting also being partially dependent on the logistics of moving a performer from one character to another.<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /><ref name=\"bfi5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NuxSzQDlaWQ |title=Horrible Histories Series Five BFI Q&A |medium=YouTube|publisher=British Film Institute|date=12 May 2013|accessdate=12 February 2014|author1=Stephenson, David |author2=Norris, Caroline |author3=with the starring cast }}</ref> Recurring characters were if at all possible played by the actor who had originated the part, leading to the development of several signature roles, as for example Baynton's [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], [[Jim Howick]]'s Shouty Man, Rickard's Bob Hale, Willbond's [[Henry VIII]], [[Martha Howe-Douglas]]' [[Elizabeth I]] and [[Simon Farnaby]]'s [[Grim Reaper|Death]].<ref name=\"popm_a\"/><ref name=\"bfi5\"/>\n\nThe performers were allowed to improvise provided that they maintained factual accuracy.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tvchoicemagazine.co.uk/interviewextra/laurence-rickard-horrible-histories | title=Interview with Laurence Rickard| work=[[TV Choice]]| date=24 May 2010 | accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Fowler, Martina}}</ref> Howick said that improvisation was actually often necessary due to the rapid-fire pace of filming, which left very little time to prepare for individual roles.<ref name=\"dog_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/yonderland/28102/mat-baynton-and-jim-howick-on-yonderland-horrible-histories-more | title=Interview with Mathew Baynton and Jim Howick | work=[[Dennis Publishing|Den of Geek]]| date=8 November 2013| accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Dobbs, Sarah}}</ref> On the other hand, both Rickard and Baynton suggest this enforced spontaneity may have ultimately worked to enhance the comedy, not least by preventing the jokes from becoming over-rehearsed.<ref name=\"express2_a\" />\n\nSix performers (Baynton, Howick, Rickard, Willbond, Howe-Douglas and Farnaby) were credited as main or starring cast throughout the show's run; a seventh, [[Sarah Hadland]], left after the second series but returned with an \"also starring\" credit for the fourth and fifth. The initial sextet appeared from Series 2 onwards as the standard face of the show at premieres and other press opportunities, and performed as a troupe for such peripheral events as the show's BBC Prom concert. They became a particularly close-knit group both personally and professionally.<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /><ref name=\"DoGinterview\" /> Eventually this led them to continue working together after ''Horrible Histories'' ceased full-time production, creating, writing and starring in the TV series ''[[Yonderland]]'' and feature film comedy ''[[Bill (2015 film)|Bill]]''.<ref name=\"DoGinterview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/yonderland/28031/laurence-rickard-and-ben-willbond-on-yonderland-horrible-histories-more | title=Interview with Laurence Rickard and Ben Willbond | work=[[Dennis Publishing|Den of Geek]]| date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Dobbs, Sarah}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/horrible-histories-launches-to-hit-the-big-screen-with-first-feature-film-untold-story-of-william-bill-shakespeare-to-be-told-8613838.html| title=Horrible Histories to hit the big screen with first feature film: Untold story of William 'Bill' Shakespeare to be told |work=The Independent | date=13 May 2013 | accessdate=4 June 2013|author=Sherwin, Adam}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:6%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Starring Actor\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:37%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Roles (recurring only)\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Mathew Baynton]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Charles II of England]], [[William Shakespeare]], host of \"Historical Fashion Fix\", [[Philip II of Spain]], [[Aristotle]], historical detective D.I. Bones, Nigel the Historical Paramedic, Emperor [[Elagabalus]], [[Guy Fawkes]], [[Menelaus]], [[Richard I of England|Richard I Lionheart]], [[Mark Antony]], [[Emperor Augustus]], [[Bartholomew Roberts|Captain Black Bart]], [[Henry I of England]], [[Charles I of England]], [[James VI and I]] (Series 1 - 4), [[Nicholas II of Russia]], [[George II of Great Britain]], [[Isaac Newton]], [[Charles VII of France]], [[Peter III of Russia]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Simon Farnaby]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Grim Reaper|Death]], [[Caligula]], historical PR agent Cliff Whiteley, [[William the Conqueror]], [[George III of Great Britain]] (Series 1 and 5 and [[BBC Proms|BBC Prom]] concert), [[James II of England]], [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley Earl of Leicester]], [[Arthur Phillip]], [[Rameses II]], [[Robert Walpole]], senior Historical Grimefighter, [[Edmond Halley]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Martha Howe-Douglas]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Elizabeth I of England]], [[Queen Victoria|Victoria of Great Britain]] (Series 2 onward), HHTV News anchorwoman Sam, [[Cleopatra VII Philopator|Cleopatra]], [[Empress Matilda]], [[Joan of Arc]], spoof of [[Karren Brady]] in \"Historical Apprentice\", [[Boudicca]], Sally the \"Historical Dating Service\" consultant\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Jim Howick]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[George IV of the United Kingdom|George IV of Great Britain]], the Shouty Man, [[Richard III of England]],  spoof of [[Alan Sugar]] in \"Historical Apprentice\", [[Nero]], [[Winston Churchill]], [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]], spoof of [[Gregg Wallace]] in \"Historical Masterchef\", Geoff the Historical Paramedic, HHTV News investigative reporter Dominic Duckworth, [[Lord Nelson]], [[Napoleon Bonaparte]], [[Henry II of England]], [[Blackbeard]], [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]], [[Samuel Pepys]], [[Wilhelm II, German Emperor]], [[Martin Luther]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Laurence Rickard]]\n|<!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation --> HHTV News special correspondent Bob Hale, [[James VI and I]] (Series 5), [[George V]], [[Draco (lawgiver)|Draco]], [[Diogenes of Sinope|Diogenes]], [[William II of England]], [[Duke of Wellington]], [[Stephen, King of England]], [[Nicholas Culpeper]], [[Henry V of England]], [[Beau Brummell]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Ben Willbond]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Henry VIII of England]], [[Alexander the Great]], HHTV News field correspondent Mike Peabody, [[Julius Caesar]], spoof of [[John Torode]] in \"Historical Masterchef\", [[George I of Great Britain]], spoof of [[John Humphrys]] in \"Historical Mastermind\", [[Pierre de Coubertin]], [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|William Cecil]],  [[Louis XVI of France]], [[William Wallace]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Sarah Hadland]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Queen Victoria|Victoria of Great Britain]] (Series 1), [[Mary I of England]], [[Nell Gwyn]], [[Anne Hyde]], [[Katharina von Bora]], [[Florence Nightingale]], presenter of \"Ready Steady Feast\" (Series 1), emergency ward nurse in \"Historical Hospital\" (Series 1), Mandy the dental assistant in \"Historical Dentist\", [[Nefertari]], narrator of \"Dodgy War Inventions\"\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n|}\n\nThe supporting cast varied considerably by series. Those performers with additional speaking parts are listed below:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:8%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Actor\n! style=\"width:18%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Appearances\n! style=\"width:35%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Roles (recurring only)\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Lawry Lewin]]\n| Series 2 to 5\n|<!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Oliver Cromwell]], spoof of [[Brian Cox (physicist)|Brian Cox]] in \"Wonders of the Historical Universe\", [[Charles Edward Stuart]], [[George III of Great Britain]] (Series 2), spoof of [[Nick Hewer]] in \"Historical Apprentice\", Dave the junior Historical Grimefighter, \"Who on Earth Are You?\" in-house genealogist Sir Francis Guesswork\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"col\"| [[Dominique Moore]]\n| Series 2 to 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Mary Seacole]], presenter of \"Ready Steady Feast\" (Series 2), HHTV presenter Fearne Polyester (spoof of [[Fearne Cotton]]), [[Rosa Parks]], emergency ward nurse in \"Historical Hospital\" (Series 2 onward), Karen the \"Historical Dating Service\" consultant\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Alice Lowe]]\n| Series 2, 3 and 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Henrietta Maria of France]], [[Marie Antoinette]], [[Matilda of Boulogne]], [[Joan of Arc]], Sue, Cliff Whiteley's secretary, HHTV News field reporter Jessica Harvey-Smythe\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Giles Terera]]\n| Series 1 to 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Presenter of \"HHTV Sport\"\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Javone Prince]]\n| Series 1\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Host of \"This is Your Reign\"\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| Lisa Devlin\n| Series 1\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Shelley the assistant at \"Historical Hairdressers\"\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Rhashan Stone]]\n| Series 3\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Richard (\"HHTV Sport\" Reporter)\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| Susie Donkin\n| Uncredited in Series 2 and 3, credited for Series 1, 4 and 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Terry Deary]]\n| Uncredited in Series 1 to 3, credited for Series 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Katy Wix]]\n| Series 1 to 4\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Steve Punt]]\n| Series 1, 2 and 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Katherine Jakeways]]\n| Series 4 and 5\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[George Sawyer]]\n| Series 1\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Nathaniel Martello-White]]\n| Series 2\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Jessica Ransom]]\n| Series 4\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Jalaal Hartley]]\n| Series 4\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->Various characters\n|}\n\nPuppeteer [[John Eccleston]], operates the [[puppet]] rat host, Rattus Rattus, whilst also supplying his voice. [[Scott Brooker]] performs additional puppetry. [[Jon Culshaw]], [[Jess Robinson]], and [[Dave Lamb]] provide various additional voice-overs and narration throughout the series.\n\nThe show has attracted several special guest stars. In the fourth series, Gatiss, Shearsmith and Pemberton of ''[[The League of Gentlemen]]'' joined the show, playing the panel of Hollywood producers for the \"Movie Pitch\" sketches. Shearsmith said, \"Mark and I independently thought it was just a brilliant show that works on a number of levels&nbsp;... There's not a weak link in the team here and it's an honour to be asked to be part of it\".<ref name=\"radiotimes\" /> Other featured guests included:\n* [[Meera Syal]] (Series 1, Storyteller in \"Twisted Fairytales\")\n* [[Alexei Sayle]] (Series 2, Arabic healer, \"Historical Hospital\")<ref name=\"bbcpress\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/05_may/13/horrible_histories.shtml | title=Horrible Histories series two debuts | publisher=BBC Press Office | work=Press Packs: Horrible Histories | date=13 May 2010 | accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Tanni Grey-Thompson]] (Series 3, herself, field reporter for \"HHTV Sport\")<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/tanni-grey-thompson-lands-role-horrible-1819228 | title=Tanni Grey-Thompson lands role in Horrible Histories TV show | work=Wales Online | date=3 July 2011 | accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n* [[David Baddiel]] (Series 2 & 3, storyteller Vincenzo Larfoff, \"Scary Stories\")<ref name=\"guardian_a\"/>\n* [[Chris Addison]] (Series 4, two different \"Historical Apprentice\" candidates)<ref name=\"express2_a\" />\n* [[Amir Khan (British boxer)|Amir Khan]] and [[Jermain Defoe]] (Series 4, as themselves in [[Sport Relief]] sketches)<ref name=\"sprelief\"/>\n* [[Al Murray]] (Series 5, various roles, notably the drummer for the [[The Smiths|Smiths]]-inspired [[Charles Dickens]] music video)<ref name=\"radiotimes1\" />\n\n==Reception==\n''Horrible Histories'' was immediately, and almost universally, greeted with critical enthusiasm.<ref name=\"bcgpress\"/> On its debut, Alice-Azania Jarvis of ''[[The Independent]]'' described the show as \"fun, filthy and genuinely engaging, in a peer-to-peer way.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-television-horrible-histories-bbc1brprofessor-reganrsquos-diet-clinic-bbc2-1669804.html|title=Last night's television: Horrible Histories|work=The Independent|date=17 April 2009|accessdate=9 February 2013|author=Jarvis, Alice-Azania }}</ref> Harry Venning in ''[[The Stage]]'' approved the \"seriously funny, beautifully performed and endlessly inventive sketches\" along with \"plenty of crowd-pleasing fart and poo gags.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/press/?ppage=3 | title=Horrible Histories review |work=[[The Stage]] | date=27 April 2009 | accessdate=12 December 2013|author=Venning, Harry}}</ref> By the second series, the show's cross-generational appeal was beginning to attract significant attention from adult media.<ref name=\"guardian3_a\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/28/horrible-histories-cbbc-grade-dent | title=Grace Dent's TV OD: Horrible Histories | work=The Guardian | date=28 May 2011 | accessdate=13 December 2013|author=Dent, Grace}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/article3025583.ece | title=Horrible Histories: the hysterical success story | work=[[The Times]]|url-access=subscription | date=May 20, 2011 | accessdate=13 December 2013 | author=Midgley, Carol}}</ref> Naomi West of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' characterised the first series as \"boundary-pushing\", suggesting that \"the bold decision to approach the series in the same way as an adult show has been the key to its success&nbsp;... [it] delivers more laughs than most post-watershed comedies.\"<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /> [[James Delingpole]] in ''[[The Spectator]]'' likewise recommended the show to viewers of all ages, saying that \"Even though there are vast quantities of entirely gratuitous fart, bottom and wee wee jokes, the cumulative effect\u2014bizarrely\u2014is one of dumbing up rather than down.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/arts/6069663/history-like-it-used-to-be/ | title=History like it used to be | work=[[The Spectator]] | date=9 June 2010 | accessdate=5 February 2014 | author=Delingpole, James}}</ref> Discussing the first two series in ''[[The Guardian]]'', television writer [[Jesse Armstrong]] said that \"Hit shows are very difficult to achieve. You need to have everything just right\u2014that's what's so terrifying. But ''Horrible Histories'' has a great cast and brilliant writers. They're also blessed with great source material. The tone is perfect and it is done in a non-patronising, engaging way\".<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\n\nClare Heal of the ''[[Daily Express]]'', in her review of the third series, praised the show's \"spot-on spoofs of modern telly\" and agreed that \"There's no particular target audience but pretty much anyone of any age will find something in there for them\".<ref name=\"express\">{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/250826/Horrible-Histories-Sands-reveal-secrets |title=Horrible Histories: Sands reveal secrets |work=[[Daily Express]]|date=6 May 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2013|author=Heal, Clare}}</ref> Kerrie Mills of [[PopMatters]] rated the first three series 9/10, opining that the show \"does also provide evidence, edgewise between the falling bodily fluids, of a sharp comic intelligence&nbsp;... in fact, it might just be one of the most successful original comedy shows to appear in years.\"<ref name=\"popm_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.popmatters.com/post/149373-horrible-histories-or-how-childrens-tv-grew-up-in-a-hurry/P0/ | title=Horrible Histories: or, how children's TV grew up in a hurry | work=[[PopMatters]] | date=9 November 2011 | accessdate=12 December 2013|author=Mills, Kerrie}}</ref> Stephen Kelly of ''The Guardian'' argued that the fourth series had definitively transcended its roots to become not just \"the best show on children's television\u2014it's one of the smartest comedies on TV\", performed by an \"astonishing cast&nbsp;... so superb that even special guest stars such as Chris Addison can look slightly out of their depth.\"<ref name=\"guardreview\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2012/apr/12/horrible-histories-comedy | title=Horrible Histories is one of the smartest comedies on TV | work=The Guardian | date=12 April 2012 | accessdate=3 October 2012|author=Kelly, Stephen}}</ref> In an article discussing the ''League of Gentlemen'' troupe's appearance in the same series, the ''[[Radio Times]]''' Gareth McLean agreed that \"despite nominally being a children's programme, ''Horrible Histories'' is one of the best sketch comedies on TV\", adding that \"ultimately, comedy performers relish [the] madcap, sometimes deliciously silly exuberance, which, thanks to the show's razorsharp writing, educates as well as entertains.\"<ref name=\"radiotimes\" /> Graeme Virtue of ''[[The Scotsman]]'' called the League's reunion a \"coup\" for the series: \"While Gatiss's American accent was pretty duff, the bickering spark between the three Gentlemen remained.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/tv-radio/television-review-derek-the-matt-lucas-awards-horrible-histories-1-2235013 |title=Television review: Horrible Histories |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=17 April 2012 |accessdate=16 December 2013 |author=Virtue, Graeme}}</ref>\n\nSarah Dempster of ''The Guardian'' said that \"Four years into its ingenious 'making history look less crap' operation&nbsp;... HH remains true to its aim, with meticulously harvested historical data + roaringly well-observed pop culture pastiches = seemingly infinite heritage lolz.\"<ref name=\"guardian_b\">{{cite web|author=Dempster, Sarah |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/may/25/horrible-histories-is-back |title=Horrible Histories is back and it's as brilliant as ever|work=The Guardian |date=25 May 2013 |accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Writing in ''The Independent'', [[Grace Dent]] commended the cast in particular, saying that the show \"has the distinct feel of a group of bright, young, erudite, writery-actory sparks having a tremendously good time.\" <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/grace-dent-on-tv-horrible-histories-cbbc-britains-got-talent-itv1-breaking-amish-tlc-8638352.html | title=Grace Dent on TV | work=The Independent | date=31 May 2013 | accessdate=12 December 2013|author=Dent, Grace}}</ref> Venning of ''The Stage'' reiterated his praise of the show, adding that \"it also has the courage to tackle potentially controversial events head on\", specifically citing the song featuring the [[Civil Rights Movement]] activist [[Rosa Parks]] as retelling her story in a \"clever, concise and accessible way without trivialising it.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/tv-radio/2013/05/tv-review-horrible-histories-the-story-of-now-up-the-women/ | title=TV review: Horrible Histories | work=[[The Stage]] | date=21 May 2013 | accessdate=13 December 2013|author=Venning, Harry}}</ref> In 2016, Margaret Lyons of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the series as \"deeply silly\", \"frequently hilarious\", and,\"very consistent\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/26/arts/television/downton-abbey-horrible-histories-what-to-watch.html|title=What You Should Watch if You Have Kids or Miss \u2018Downton Abbey\u2019|last=Lyons|first=Margaret|date=August 26, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Historical accuracy===\nMost criticism of the show revolves around the accuracy and presentation of its factual content. The TV series, like the books, has been used by educators as a classroom aid<ref name=\"tbivision_a\" /> and was endorsed by UK Education Secretary [[Michael Gove]] as useful for spotlighting \"neglected periods of history.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/10542727/Michael-Gove-criticises-disconnected-history-lessons.html | title=Michael Gove criticises 'disconnected' history lessons | work=The Telegraph| date=30 December 2013 | accessdate=3 January 2014|author=Paton, Graeme}}</ref> However, writing after the final episode, [[Simon Hoggart]] in ''The Spectator'' noted that \"There has been some whipped-up controversy about ''Horrible Histories''\", adding that \"where the books make a rudimentary attempt to teach history as a series of interconnected events, the television show is basically gags, chiefly about defecation, gluttony, murder and torture. It's quite amusing, though whether it will pique an interest in the subject, or\u2014as some say\u2014merely encourage children to learn more about defecation, gluttony, murder and torture, we cannot know.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Hoggart, Simon |url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/arts/6050573/shakespeare-in-school/ |title=Shakespeare in school|work=[[The Spectator]] |date=2 June 2010|accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nMore specifically, in September 2014, responding to a complaint from the Nightingale Society, the BBC Trust determined that the show had breached editorial guidelines in the sketch highlighting the controversy surrounding Mary Seacole's role in nursing history. In this sketch, Florence Nightingale says that she rejected the Jamaican-born Seacole's application to Nightingale's Crimean nursing corps because it was open to \"British girls\" only. This was held to be imputing racially discriminatory motives to Nightingale\u2014and thus implying them to be historical fact\u2014without sufficient proof. In response, the BBC pulled the offending sketch from their website and announced it would be removed from future showings of the episode.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC rapped over Horrible Histories Florence Nightingale sketch|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29426242|accessdate=22 October 2014|work=BBC News|date=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a 20th-anniversary retrospective of the franchise in ''The Telegraph'', [[David Horspool]], the history editor of the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'', defended the show's overall viewpoint, saying, \"There's no particular reason why grown-up historians shouldn't like ''Horrible Histories'' too&nbsp;... They simplify, and they have a definite point of view, but all historians are guilty of that to some degree.\" He further said that \"Getting children interested in the past isn't necessarily easy, and ''Horrible Histories'' does it extremely effectively\u2014and those who come to history because it's fun seem far more likely to stay with it in the long run.\"<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /> Writing for entertainment website DorkAdore, Anna Lowman added that \"Terry Deary had the fine idea of getting kids into history by giving the facts a human face and a joke or two&nbsp;... The producers of the CBBC show have perfectly transferred Deary's ethos to television.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dorkadore.com/film-tv/horrible-histories-and-king-of-what-weve-been-watching/ | title=TV Reviews: Horrible Histories with Stephen Fry | work=Dork Adore | date=20 June 2011 | accessdate=13 December 2013 | author=Lowman, Anna | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216182952/http://www.dorkadore.com/film-tv/horrible-histories-and-king-of-what-weve-been-watching/ | archivedate=16 December 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe recut for BBC1 with Fry as host drew particular criticism as to whether its educational methods were suited to an adult demographic. ''[[History Today]]'' editor Paul Lay called the idea \"frightening\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.historytoday.com/blog/2011/06/horrible-histories-suitable-adults | title=Is 'Horrible Histories' suitable for adults? | work=[[History Today]]| date=20 June 2011 | accessdate=15 February 2014 | author=Lay, Paul}}</ref> Historian and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party MP]] [[Tristram Hunt]], while admitting that he had not yet actually seen the programme,<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> voiced his concerns that the show's content was not \"challenging and stimulating\" enough for the BBC, adding that \"For children, ''Horrible Histories'' is an exciting aid to engage with the guts and gore of the past, but there are more sophisticated, populist ways of getting people involved in history than this. I'm in favour of populism, but there has to be a bit of depth to it.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000418/ | title=Horrible Histories to be remade for adult audience | work=British Comedy Guide | date=5 December 2011 | accessdate=13 December 2013|author=Wolf, Ian}}</ref>\n\nOther critics have taken a more lenient view. Historian and television presenter Dan Snow described the show's ''modus operandi'' as \"one step above ''Blackadder'', but that's fine&nbsp;... it plays to stereotypes, but it's fantastic as entry-level history.\"<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Writing in ''The Independent'', [[Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster)|Tom Sutcliffe]] noted that \"As a grown-up you might quibble with the fact that they don't always distinguish between things that genuinely are true and the things that people would like to be (sadly, there's no hard evidence that [[Aeschylus]] was brained by a tortoise dropped by an overflying eagle)\", but added that \"children and adults alike should enjoy the gleefully anachronistic way in which the information is presented.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-tv--coronation-street-itv1-the-5-oclock-show-with-peter-andre-channel-4-horrible-histories-cbbc-1988703.html|title=Last Night's TV|date=2 June 2010|work=The Independent|accessdate=17 July 2010|author=Sutcliffe, Tom}}</ref> Dent in ''The Guardian'', while conceding what she called the show's  \"frankly slapdash, dumbed-down approach to history\", also argued that \"in ''Horrible Histories'' there are always serious messages lurking amid the silliness.\"<ref name=\"guardian3_a\" />\n\n===Ratings===\nIn its debut week of 15 June 2009, the show topped the UK children's TV viewing figures with 191,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scholastic.co.uk/department/home/blogs/7741 |title=Horrible TV series back at the top |work=[[Scholastic Books|Scholastic Books UK]] |date=15 June 2009 |accessdate=27 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727024243/http://www.scholastic.co.uk/department/home/blogs/7741 |archive-date=27 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The first series reached a viewing peak of 50% of UK children aged 6\u201312,<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /> while the second was watched by 34% of UK children aged 6\u201312, or 1.6 million total.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/organgrinder/2011/may/25/horrible-histories-comedy | title=Horrible Histories: comedy for all ages | work=The Guardian| date=25 May 2011 | accessdate=12 December 2013|author=Brown, Maggie}}</ref> Throughout its run, the show routinely ranked at or near the top of the CBBC ratings, reaching a peak of 548,000 viewers for Episode 10 of Series 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Viewing data: Top 10 |url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10? |work=[[BARB]] data |accessdate=9 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718204656/http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n''Horrible Histories'' received numerous domestic and international awards and nominations, including several [[BAFTA Children's Awards]], two [[British Comedy Awards]] and a [[Rose d'Or]] Award for Best Children's Programme. It is the first children's programme to win a British Comedy Award<ref name=\"BCA 2010\"/> and four successive children's BAFTAs, for Best Comedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-25085710|title=''Horrible Histories'' wins fourth consecutive children's BAFTA |work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref> In 2013 the show was also named in a ''Radio Times'' poll of all-time greatest British children's TV series, and was cited at No. 8 in a similar Top 50 list presented later the same year by [[Channel Five]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/peppa-pig-and-bob-the-builder-join-ranks-of-top-childrens-tv-show-8737529.html | title=Peppa Pig, Bob the Builder join ranks of top children's TV show | work=The Independent| date=30 July 2013 | accessdate=11 December 2013|author=Noah, Sherna}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/channel-5-reveals-greatest-kids-tv-shows-results/039007 | title=Channel 5 reveals Greatest Kids TV Shows results | work=Licensing.biz | date=12 November 2013 | accessdate=14 February 2014 | author=Langsworthy, Billy}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+ Awards and nominations for ''Horrible Histories''\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Award\n!scope=\"col\"|Title\n!scope=\"col\"|Recipient\n!scope=\"col\"|Result\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\"|2009\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Factual Programme\n|Caroline Norris, [[Chloe Thomas]], Steve Connelly\n|{{nominated}}<ref name=\"awards.bafta\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2009/childrens/ |title=Children's BAFTA award winners and nominees in 2009|work=[[BAFTA]] website|date= |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Writing\n|The Writing Team\n|{{nominated}}<ref name=\"awards.bafta\" />\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Award\n|Best Children's Programme\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nominated}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/sites/default/files/pdfs/PressReleaseRTSProgrammeAwardsWinnersFINAL.pdf |title=RTS Announces Winners for the Programme Awards 2009 |publisher=[[Royal Television Society]] |date=16 March 2010 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"8\"| 2010\n|[[Association for International Broadcasting|AIB]] Award\n|Best Children's Factual Programme or Series\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|title=AIB announces winners of the 2010 AIBs|url=http://www.aib.org.uk/aib-announces-winners-of-the-2010-aibs/|work=[[Association for International Broadcasting]]|date=10 November 2010|accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Comedy\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"3B\"/>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Performer\n|Jim Howick\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"3B\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11860702|title=Three children's BAFTAs for ''Horrible Histories''|work=[[BBC News Online]]|date=29 November 2010|accessdate=9 February 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Writer\n|The Writing Team\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"3B\"/>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Kids' Vote \u2013 Television\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2010/childrens/bafta-kids-vote-2010-top-10s-television |title=2010 Children's BAFTA Kids' Vote \u2013 Television|work=[[BAFTA]] website |date= |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|British Comedy Award\n|Best Sketch Show\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"BCA 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000446/miranda_leads_bca_2010_winners/ |title=Miranda leads winners at British Comedy Awards 2010|work=British Comedy Guide|date=23 January 2011 |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|Prix Jeunesse International Award\n|Best 7\u201311 Non fiction\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prixjeunesse.de/themen/festival/2010/prize_winners/prize_winners_2010.pdf | title=PRIX JEUNESSE INTERNATIONAL 2010 Prize Winners | work=Prix Jeunesse Foundation | date=2 June 2010 | accessdate=8 February 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222070756/http://www.prixjeunesse.de/themen/festival/2010/prize_winners/prize_winners_2010.pdf | archive-date=22 February 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Award\n|Best Children's Programme\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/rts-programme-awards-2010 |title=RTS Programme Awards 2010|publisher=Royal Television Society |date= |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"10\"| 2011\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Comedy\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"BAFTA 2011\"/>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Performer\n|Martha Howe-Douglas\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"BAFTA 2011\"/>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Writing\n|The Writing Team\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"BAFTA 2011\"/>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Kids Vote \u2013 Television\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"BAFTA 2011\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2011/childrens/ |title=Children's BAFTA award winners and nominees in 2011|work=[[BAFTA]] website|date= |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|British Comedy Award\n|Best Sketch Show\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|title=British Comedy Awards 2011 winners announced|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000711/british_comedy_awards_2011_winners_list/|work=British Comedy Guide|accessdate=2 November 2012|date=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|Broadcast Award\n|Best Children's Programme\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Wightman, Catriona|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a301830/in-full-broadcast-awards-2011-winners.html |title=In Full: Broadcast Awards 2011 Winners \u2013 TV News |work=[[Digital Spy]] |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Acting\n|Cast of ''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA11\" />\n|-\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Kids Non Animation or Mixed Series\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA11\">{{cite web|title=And the Kidscreen Awards go to&nbsp;...|url=http://kidscreen.com/2011/02/18/and-the-kidscreen-awards-go-to/|work=Kidscreen|accessdate=2 November 2012|date=18 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910114038/http://kidscreen.com/2011/02/18/and-the-kidscreen-awards-go-to/|archive-date=10 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Writing\n|The Writing Team\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA11\"/>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Award\n|Best Children's Programme\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9111107/Nominees-for-the-Royal-Television-Society-Programme-Awards-announced.html | title=Nominees for the 2011 Royal Television Society Programme Awards announced | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=20 March 2012 | accessdate=9 February 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row\" rowspan=\"12\"| 2012\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Comedy\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"awards.bafta_a\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2012/childrens/ |title=Children's BAFTA award winners and nominees in 2012|work=[[BAFTA]] website|date= |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Performer\n|Mathew Baynton\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"awards.bafta_a\" />\n|-\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Writer\n|The Writing Team\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"awards.bafta_a\" />\n|-\n|British Comedy Award\n|Best Sketch Show\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000999/british_comedy_awards_2012_winners/ |title=British Comedy Awards 2012 \u2013 Full Results |work=British Comedy Guide|date=12 December 2012 |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|Broadcast Award\n|Best Children's Programme\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastawards.co.uk/shortlist2012 |title=Broadcast Awards \u2013 Shortlist 2012 |work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]] |accessdate=18 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304121711/http://www.broadcastawards.co.uk/shortlist2012 |archivedate=4 March 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Acting\n|Cast of ''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA12\">{{cite web|title=And the 2012 Kidscreen Awards go to&nbsp;... |url=http://kidscreen.com/2012/02/09/and-the-2012-kidscreen-awards-go-to/|work=Kidscreen|accessdate=2 November 2012|date=9 February 2012|author=Castleman, Lana}}</ref>\n|-\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Writing\n|The Writing Team\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA12\"/>\n|-\n|Rose d'Or Award\n|Best Children's Programme\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/00000815/rose_dor_2012_comedy_winners_announced/ |title=Rose d'Or 2012 comedy winners announced|work=British Comedy Guide |date=10 May 2012 |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Craft & Design Award\n|Costume Design Entertainment & Non Drama Productions\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/rts-announces-winners-craft-design-awards-20112012 |title=RTS ANNOUNCES WINNERS FOR CRAFT & DESIGN AWARDS 2011/2012 |publisher=Royal Television Society |accessdate=18 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405164519/http://www.rts.org.uk/rts-announces-winners-craft-design-awards-20112012 |archivedate=5 April 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Craft & Design Award\n|Effects Picture Enhancement\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Craft & Design Award\n|Production Design Entertainment & Non Drama Productions\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n|-\n|Writers' Guild Award\n|Best Children's TV Script\n|The Writing Team\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writersguild.org.uk/news-a-features/general/323-writers-guild-awards-2012-shortlist |title=Writers' Guild Awards 2012 shortlists |work=[[Writers' Guild of Great Britain|UK Writer's Guild]] |date=14 September 2012 |accessdate=18 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513050354/http://www.writersguild.org.uk/news-a-features/general/323-writers-guild-awards-2012-shortlist |archivedate=13 May 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"| 2013\n|BAFTA Children's Award\n|Best Comedy\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2013/childrens|title=Children's BAFTA award winners and nominees in 2013|work=[[BAFTA]] website|date= |accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|British Comedy Award\n|Best Sketch Show\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/british-comedy-awards-2013-list-of-nominees-in-full-8980581.html | title=British Comedy Awards 2013: List of nominees in full | work=The Independent| date=3 December 2013 | accessdate=9 February 2014 | author=Denham, Jess}}</ref>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Craft & Design Award\n|Best Picture Enhancement\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{nom}}<ref name=\"RTS\"/>\n|-\n|Royal Television Society Craft & Design Award\n|Best Tape and Film Editing: Entertainment and Situation Comedy\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"RTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/winners-cda |title=RTS Craft & Design Awards 2012/2013 |publisher=Royal Television Society |date=19 November 2013 |accessdate=17 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221315/http://www.rts.org.uk/winners-cda |archivedate=17 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\"| 2014\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Acting\n|Cast of ''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA14\"/>\n|-\n|Kidscreen Award\n|Best Kids Non Animation or Mixed Series\n|''Horrible Histories''\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA14\">{{cite web|title=And the 2014 award winners are&nbsp;... |url=http://kidscreen.com/2014/02/11/and-the-2014-kidscreen-awards-winners-are/|work=Kidscreen|accessdate=25 February 2014|date=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|KidScreen Award\n|Best Writing\n|The Writing Team\n|{{won}}<ref name=\"KSA14\"/>\n|}\n\n==DVD and online releases==\nAll five series of the original show, plus the \"Scary (Halloween) Special\", \"Ridiculous Romance\" & the \"Frightful First World War Special\" and \"Horrible Christmas\" have been released on [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] DVD by 2entertain for the BBC, both individually and as boxed sets.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/s/ref=sr_st?keywords=horrible+histories&qid=1393458926&rh=n%3A283926%2Ck%3Ahorrible+histories&sort=relevancerank | title=\"Horrible Histories\" in DVD & Blu-ray | work=[[Amazon UK]] | accessdate=26 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nEach series, as well as the \"Scary Special\" and \"Sport Special\", are also available for download from the UK iTunes store.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/tv-season/horrible-histories-series-1-3/id642399790 | title=Horrible Histories on iTunes | work=[[iTunes Store|iTunes UK Store]] | accessdate=26 February 2014}}</ref> As of February 2014, all episodes from Series 1\u20133 were available for download to American audiences on Amazon.com \"Instant Video\" service.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_i_0_15?url=search-alias%3Dinstant-video&field-keywords=horrible%20histories&sprefix=horrible+histor%2Cinstant-video%2C349&rh=i%3Ainstant-video%2Ck%3Ahorrible%20histories | title=Horrible Histories Series 1\u20133 |  work=[[Amazon Video]] | accessdate=26 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-offs==\nIn 2011, a spinoff game show, ''[[Horrible Histories: Gory Games]]'', was launched on CBBC. Likewise coproduced by Lion TV and Citrus, the show is co-hosted by [[Dave Lamb]] with puppet Rattus Rattus and includes cameos from many of the parent show's cast. As of 2013, the show had aired three full series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/programme/cpsr8/hh-gory-games/episodeguide |title=Episode Guide: HH Gory Games |work=[[Radio Times]] |accessdate=7 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222003543/http://www.radiotimes.com/programme/cpsr8/hh-gory-games/episodeguide |archivedate=22 February 2014 }}</ref> For summer 2011, the show was repackaged for adult Sunday-night audiences as ''[[Horrible Histories with Stephen Fry]]'', a six-part \"best of\" compilation for main channel [[BBC One]]. The show featured a selection of sketches and songs from the first two series as chosen by the producers of the parent show, with Fry replacing the puppet rat as presenter.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories_stephen_fry/ | title=Horrible Histories With Stephen Fry | work=British Comedy Guide| accessdate=7 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==2015 revival and specials==\nIn 2015, the [[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|series returned]] with a new cast in a revised format. Episodes centred around the life of one prominent historical figure played by an established comedy actor. It was in 2016 that a seventh series began with just three specials before  the full series in 2017. The three specials marked anniversaries through the year: 400 years since Shakespeare died, the BBCs 'Love to Read' campaign and 350 years since the Great Fire of London. There was a slight change in cast where the main stars [[Jalaal Hartley]], [[Tom Stourton]] and [[Jessica Ransom]] continued with new members. This was the first series where none of the main original cast were present.\n\n==Films==\nOn 18 September 2015 ''[[Bill (2015 film)|Bill]]'', a 2015 BBC comedy film based loosely around the early life of [[William Shakespeare]], was released. The film, though not officially related to the series, reunited and starred the original core performers of ''Horrible Histories'' in starring roles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/bbc-films-bill-press-release.html|title=Stars of Horrible Histories to make Shakespeare film|date=22 March 2013|work=BBC Media Centre|accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/film/bill/details/ | title=Bill: production details | publisher=comedy.co.uk | work=British Comedy Guide | accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, it was announced that [[Altitude Film Distribution|Altitude Film Entertainment]] and Citrus Films were producing a film adaptation. It was directed by [[Dominic Brigstocke]] and was set in Roman Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2017/10/12/38130/horrible_histories_heads_to_the_big_screen|title=Horrible Histories heads to the big screen : News 2017 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide|first=Powder Blue Internet Business|last=Solutions|website=www.chortle.co.uk}}</ref> The film, ''[[Horrible Histories: The Movie \u2013 Rotten Romans]]'' was released July 26, 2019. The original cast of the TV series were not involved, although members of the revival cast were. The film received mostly positive reviews, earning a 69% approval score on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/horrible-histories-movie-works/|title=Horrible Histories Movie In The Works|first=James|last=White|date=3 October 2018|website=Empire}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|EN-Horrible Histories (2009 TV series)-article.ogg|2018-06-16}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{British Comedy Guide|tv|horrible_histories|Horrible Histories}}\n* [https://www.peterlorrecompanion.com/yonderlanders.html \"Yonderlanders: Celebrating the collective art of Mathew Baynton, Simon Farnaby, Martha Howe-Douglas, Jim Howick, Laurence Rickard, and Ben Willbond\"]\n{{Horrible Histories}}\n{{Horrible Histories troupe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horrible Histories (2009 Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:2000s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2009 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2013 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:BBC children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC television comedy]]\n[[Category:BBC television sketch shows]]\n[[Category:Children's comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Horrible Histories]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:British television programmes featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British television sketch shows]]\n[[Category:Children's sketch comedy]]\n[[Category:Surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:CBBC programmes]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the original series|the 2015 revival|Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n\n| image                    = HHlive-actionlogo.png\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = Title logo (with background used from Series 2 - 5)\n| genre                    = Musical<br>Comedy<br>Sketch comedy\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = ''[[Horrible Histories (book series)|Horrible Histories]]''<br>by [[Terry Deary]]<br>[[Peter Hepplewhite]]<br>Neil Tonge\n| developer                = [[Dominic Brigstocke]]<br>Caroline Norris\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Steve Connelly\n* [[Dominic Brigstocke]] (Series 2 to 4)\n* Chloe Thomas (Series 1 and 4)\n}}\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mathew Baynton]]\n* [[Simon Farnaby]]\n* [[Sarah Hadland]]\n* [[Martha Howe-Douglas]]\n* [[Jim Howick]]\n* [[Lawry Lewin]]\n* [[Alice Lowe]]\n* [[Laurence Rickard]]\n* [[Ben Willbond]]\n}}\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = [[John Eccleston]] (Rattus Rattus)<br />[[Jon Culshaw]]<br />[[Jess Robinson]]<br />[[Dave Lamb]]\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = [[Richie Webb]]<br>Matt Katz\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = Richie Webb\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 5\n| num_series               = 8\n| num_episodes             = 105 regular episodes, 10 full-length specials\n| list_episodes            = List of Horrible Histories episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Richard Bradley\n* [[Kim Shillinglaw]] (Series 1)\n* Alison Gregory (Series 2 to 4)\n* Melissa Hardinge (Series 4 and 5)\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Caroline Norris\n* Giles Pilbrow\n* Dominic Brigstocke (Series 1)\n* Imogen Cooper (Series 3 and 4)\n}}\n| editor                   = \n| cinematography           = Peter Edwards\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 28 minutes\n| company                  = Lion TV<br />Citrus Television (Series 2 onwards)\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[CBBC]]<br />[[CBBC HD]]\n| network                  = \n| picture_format           = [[High-definition television|HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = 16 April 2009\n| last_aired               = 4 August 2014\n| followed_by              = ''[[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|Horrible Histories Specials]]''\n| related                  = ''[[Horrible Histories: Gory Games]]''<br />''[[Horrible Histories with Stephen Fry]]''\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbbc/shows/horrible-histories\n| production_website       = http://www.liontv.com/London/Productions/Horrible-Histories\n}}\n'''''Horrible Histories''''' is a British children's live-action [[historical]] and [[Musical film|musical]] [[sketch comedy]] television series, based on the [[Horrible Histories (book series)|bestselling books of the same name]] by [[Terry Deary]]. The show was produced for [[CBBC]] by [[Lion Television]] with Citrus Television and ran from 2009 to 2013 for five series of thirteen half-hour episodes, with additional one-off seasonal and Olympic specials.\n\nThe TV show carries over the graphic style and much of the content of the [[Horrible Histories (book series)|''Horrible Histories'' book series]]. It maintains the franchise's overall irreverent but accurate focus on the dark, gruesome or scatological aspects of British and other [[Western world]] history, spanning from the [[Stone Age]] to the post-[[World War II]] era. Individual historical eras or civilisations are defined and named as in the books, with sketches from several different time periods combined within a single episode. [[Live-action]] sketches\u2014which often parody other UK media or celebrities\u2014and music videos are intercut with animations and quizzes. The starring troupe are [[Mathew Baynton]], [[Simon Farnaby]], [[Martha Howe-Douglas]], [[Jim Howick]], [[Laurence Rickard]], [[Sarah Hadland]] and [[Ben Willbond]], alongside a large supporting cast headed by [[Katy Wix]], [[Lawry Lewin]], [[Alice Lowe]] and [[Dominique Moore]]. The black rat puppet \"host\", Rattus Rattus, appears in short bridging segments, explaining the factual basis for each sketch.\n\nThe [[Horrible Histories troupe|creative team]] was largely recruited from the mainstream adult UK comedy scene. They took inspiration from such quintessentially British historical-comedy classics as ''[[Blackadder]]'' and the [[Monty Python]] films. The series was a critical and ratings success, eventually gaining a wide all ages audience through its non-condescending and inclusive approach. It has won numerous domestic and international awards and has been named among the greatest British children's television series of all time.\n\nIn 2011, a spin-off game show, ''[[Horrible Histories: Gory Games]]'', was launched on CBBC. In the same year, the original show was repackaged for main channel [[BBC One]] as ''[[Horrible Histories with Stephen Fry]]'', with [[Stephen Fry|Fry]] replacing the puppet, Rattus Rattus, as presenter. [[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|A new series of special episodes]] began airing in 2015, featuring a new format and cast. Although the original series has ended, it continues to be frequently repeated on the [[CBBC Channel]] daily.\n\n==Background==\n''Horrible Histories'' is based on [[Horrible Histories (book series)|the British children's historical-comedy book series]] by [[Terry Deary]], first published by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic UK]] in 1993 and since expanded into a [[Horrible Histories|multimedia franchise]]. The books and subsequent spin-off materials are intended to pique young children's interest in history via short, factually based but humorously told anecdotes highlighting aspects of the subject not usually covered in more traditional educational sources.<ref name=\"scanlon\">{{cite journal | title=History beyond the academy: humor and horror in children's history books | journal=New Review of Children's Literature and Librarianship, 16:2, 69\u201391|volume = 16| issue=2| pages=69\u201391|year=2011| author=Scanlon, Margaret| doi=10.1080/13614541.2010.540197 }}</ref>\n\nLionTV executive producer Richard Bradley, whose company had previously produced several adult history-themed programmes and whose son was a fan of the ''Horrible Histories'' books, was the initial driving force behind a new TV adaptation.<ref name=\"guardian_a\">{{cite web|author=Hickman, Leo |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/mar/17/horrible-histories-huge-hit |title=How Horrible Histories became a huge hit|work=The Guardian |date=17 March 2011|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Deary was initially sceptical, having had a negative experience with the [[Horrible Histories (2001 TV series)|2001 animated series]], which had only loosely incorporated his concept. He finally agreed to the new project on the condition that it be explicitly \"horrible, funny and true\". While disclaiming any active role in developing the subsequent series, he would eventually contribute to the writing as well as appearing in several small roles.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\n\nThe producers were determined that the show be respectful of audience expectations for the Horrible Histories brand, maintaining its familiar visual style and content as far as possible. Early concepts for bringing it to the screen involved framing or interpretive devices, including a ghostly train carrying children into the past, or a wizard storyteller to act as their guide. Eventually Bradley with producer/director [[Dominic Brigstocke]] concluded that the material was strong enough to stand on its own, so they developed, in consultation with CBBC executives, a live-action sketch-comedy showcase.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Once the writing was underway, the producers further discovered that sticking as closely as possible to the historical truth made it easier for them to find the humour within it. They then introduced a comedy style relying on parodies of familiar modern media [[Convention (norm)|conventions]] as a means of making these historical details more immediately accessible.<ref name=\"bcg_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/about/ | title=About: Horrible Histories | work=[[British Comedy Guide]] | accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nTo do the material full justice, Brigstocke and series producer Caroline Norris used their industry contacts to put together a creative team consisting mostly of veterans of the adult UK comedy community.<ref name=\"bcg_a\" /><ref name=\"telegraph_a\"/> The BBC readily agreed to this cross-demographic experiment. They also approved the adoption\u2014insofar as was possible in a programme aimed at young children\u2014of the core franchise precept of \"history with the nasty bits left in\",<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9857326/Horrible-Histories-20-years-of-entertaining-children.html | title=Horrible Histories: 20 years of entertaining children |work=The Daily Telegraph | date=21 February 2013 | accessdate=10 December 2013| author=Preston, Richard}}</ref> which frequently involved \"[[Gross out|gross-out]]\"-style bodily function humour and comic violence.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"telegraph_a\"/>\n\nThe new creative team, while avoiding references aimed specifically at adults, was determined not to adapt the humour to children or otherwise patronise their audience. Instead, they sought to make the best use possible of the material.<ref name=\"express_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/249426/Horrible-Histories-A-funny-way-to-learn | title=Horrible Histories: a funny way to learn |work=[[The Daily Express|The Sunday Express]] |date=29 May 2011| accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Stephenson, David}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcint\">{{cite AV media| title=Interview with Laurence Rickard and Mathew Baynton|work=[[BBC News]] | date=2 June 2010 <!--| accessdate=18 December 2013 No longer available on the BBC website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odo42C6mf4U-->}}</ref> Norris said that her goal was \"to make a show that people would say was too good for children&nbsp;... we started out with really high ambitions.\"<ref name=\"bfi4\"/> To that end, adult historical satires such as ''[[Blackadder]]'' and the [[Monty Python]] films were shown at the first writers' meeting to demonstrate the proposed tone, and these influences would be visible throughout the show's run.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"telegraph_a\">{{cite news|title=How Horrible Histories grew up to be a hit comedy show |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/7765195/How-Horrible-Histories-grew-up-to-be-a-hit-comedy-show.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=17 July 2010|date=25 May 2010|author=West, Naomi}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcint\" /><ref name=\"radiotimes\">{{cite web|author=McLean, Gareth|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-04-09/why-did-the-league-of-gentlemen-choose-to-reform-on-horrible-histories |title=Why did the League of Gentlemen choose to reform on Horrible Histories? |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=9 April 2012|accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\nOnce the first series had aired and it was realised that the overall approach was working well, the creative team built on and significantly expanded the scope of the comedy elements for the second.<ref name=\"bcg_a\"/><ref name=\"express_a\" /> This trend continued through each subsequent series. The net result was a show that immediately appealed to young children while also gaining the increasing respect\u2014and viewership\u2014of older audiences.<ref name=\"bcgpress\">{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/press/ | title='Horrible Histories' in the press |work=British Comedy Guide| accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{Main|List of Horrible Histories (2009 TV series) episodes|l1=List of Horrible Histories episodes}}\n\nThe divisions by historical era or civilisation in the book series are carried over in the TV show, focusing on events in or directly affecting [[Great Britain]] and (to a lesser extent) the larger [[Western world]]. The [[Incan Empire|Inca]] and [[Aztec]] empires are also featured in later series.<ref name=\"popm_a\"/> Sketches are grouped under these divisions, named as in the books, beginning with the Savage [[Stone Age]] and including among others the Cut-throat [[Celts]], Awful [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptians]], Groovy [[Ancient Greece|Greeks]], Rotten [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], Vicious [[Vikings]], Measly [[Middle Ages]], Terrible [[Tudor period|Tudors]], Slimy [[Stuart period|Stuarts]], Gorgeous [[Georgian era|Georgians]] and Vile [[Victorians]]. The timeline for the most part ended at the Woeful Second World War.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"comedy\"/> During the fifth and final series the show featured a handful of significant post-World War II (or \"Troublesome Twentieth Century\") events, including the civil rights movement and the [[Space Race]] between the US and the USSR. The most recent event referenced was the 1969 [[Apollo 11|Apollo 11 Moon landing]].<ref name=\"bfi5\" />\n\n[[File:Horrible Histories animated title cards.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Typical examples of the title cards with animated characters, based on the art style of the books, that introduced sketches]]\n\nEach named division has its own title card that appears before each sketch (or group of sketches) set in that era or civilisation, along with a short introductory animation featuring a period-appropriate character. Throughout each sketch, small pop-up signs are used to affirm the truth (or otherwise) of any particularly implausible-seeming concepts mentioned onscreen.<ref name=\"popm_a\"/> The live-action material is intercut with short animated sketches, quizzes and interludes with puppet \"host\" Rattus Rattus (performed by [[John Eccleston]]), who addresses the viewer directly as a presenter, commenting on and clarifying the factual basis behind the humour. Rattus also occasionally holds up pop-up signs himself during sketches.<ref name=\"comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/ |title=Horrible Histories|work=British Comedy Guide|date= |accessdate=27 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/horrible-histories | title=Review: Horrible Histories | work=[[Common Sense Media]]| accessdate=3 March 2014 | author=Ashby, Emily| date=2014-02-28 }}</ref>\n\nSketches were filmed ''en masse'' and then cut into episodes by the producers based on creative rather than chronological or other educational considerations, in the manner of a more traditional sketch-comedy series.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /><ref name=\"FULLSESSION\"/> They often fall under a recurring banner\u2014usually with its own short title sequence\u2014but otherwise vary widely in length, visual style and approach. Many are recognisable parodies of other popular media or celebrities, in formats ranging from spoof commercials to mock TV shows, newscasts, magazines, video games and film trailers.<ref name=\"bcg_a\"/> Notable parody inspirations included ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|Masterchef]]'', ''[[Wife Swap (UK TV series)|Wife Swap]]'', ''[[Come Dine with Me]]'' and ''[[The Apprentice (TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\"/><ref name=\"guardreview\"/> \"Horrible Histories Movie Pitch\", in which historical figures pitch their life stories to a panel of Hollywood producers played by ''[[The League of Gentlemen|League of Gentlemen]]'' actors [[Mark Gatiss]], [[Steve Pemberton]] and [[Reece Shearsmith]], used the format of a former commercial campaign for [[Orange (UK)#Orange Gold Spots|Orange's cinema reminders to turn mobiles off]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/horrible-histories-cbbc-meets-royston-vasey-7621912.html | title=CBBC meets Royston Vasey | work=[[The Independent]] | date=6 August 2012 | accessdate=16 February 2014 | author=Kelly, Stephen}}</ref>\n\nThe show also created several popular recurring characters and concepts, notably \"Stupid Deaths\", in which a skeletal, platinum-blond [[Grim Reaper]] amuses himself while processing souls for admittance to the afterlife by forcing candidates from throughout history to relate the embarrassing details of their demise.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /><ref name=\"guardian3_a\" /> HHTV News' Bob Hale and his eccentric-but-erudite in-studio reports provide a broader picture on historical events (such as the [[Wars of the Roses]] and the [[French Revolution]]), in a style reminiscent of presenter [[Peter Snow]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/home/digital-editions/broadcast-hot-100-2012/5056710.article | title=The Horrible Histories team | publisher=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]| work=Broadcast Hot 100 2012 supplement| date=23 May 2013 | accessdate=17 February 2014 | author=Parker, Robin, ed. | pages=17}}</ref><ref name=\"djsketches\">{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/broadcasters/horrible-histories-jubilee-sketches-will-never-be-aired/5043199.article|title=''Horrible Histories'' Jubilee sketches will never be aired|work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|author=Parker, Robin| date=11 June 2012|accessdate=17 February 2014|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The \"Shouty Man\", a parody of a typically ebullient [[infomercial]] host (like [[Neil Burgess (actor)|Barry Scott]]), pitches unusual historical products.<ref name=\"bcg_a\"/>\n\n===Music===\nOriginal music plays a significant role in the show and its popularity; \"Music from ''Horrible Histories''\" was chosen as the [[Horrible Histories Prom|2011 theme]] of the [[The Proms|BBC Proms]]' annual children's concert.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|author=Brogan, Benedict|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/proms/8674648/BBC-Prom-2011-Prom-20-Horrible-histories-Albert-Hall-review.html |title=BBC Prom 2011: Prom 20: Horrible Histories, Albert Hall, review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=1 August 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref> Alongside various short intro themes and commercial jingles, each episode{{refn|With the exception of Episode 5 of Series 1, produced before the music became a priority as described below.|group=note}} and each special contains at least one longer comedy song centred around a particular historical figure or theme and performed by the cast in appropriate character.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" />\n\nIn the first series, the songs generally had no particular satirical slant, and were often intercut with sketches from the same era. However, after the creative team noted the critical and popular success of the major exception (\"Born 2 Rule\", which featured [[House of Hanover|King Georges I\u2013IV]] performing in the style of a [[boyband]]) the decision was taken from the second series onwards to continue in that vein.<ref name=\"express_a\" /> Historical concepts were matched to a diverse range of modern musical references, and the results were showcased as self-contained music video parodies. The thirteenth episode of the second and each subsequent series was retooled as a \"Savage Songs\" special, featuring a compilation of that series' outstanding videos.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/episodes/ | title=Horrible Histories: Episode Guide| work=British Comedy Guide | accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe songs have since become among the most critically and popularly acclaimed elements of the show, especially among its adult audience. Commentators cite the apt cleverness of the various historical/musical parody match-ups, and the complexity and skill with which the musical elements are executed.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" /><ref name=\"telegraph\" /><ref name=\"radiotimes1\">{{cite web|author=Seale, Jack|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-06-06/horrible-histories-5-brilliant-songs-from-series-5 |title=Horrible Histories: Five brilliant songs from Series 5|work=[[Radio Times]] |date=6 June 2013|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Principal composer [[Richie Webb]] confirms that the songs became more sophisticated as a result of the show's increasing popularity with older viewers, as well as the demands of increased visibility online.<ref name=\"radiotimes1\" /> Many of the videos have earned standalone popularity on YouTube.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" />\n\nThe videos tend to run about three minutes, with two significant exceptions. \"The English Kings and Queens\", from the third series, lists all of the [[British monarchs]] since [[William the Conqueror]], using a [[Chas & Dave]]-inspired [[cumulative song|cumulative]] format.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" />{{refn|Listen to an audio clip (uploaded by the composer) [https://soundcloud.com/richiewebb/horrible-histories-kings-and here]|group=note}} The creative team wrote the song to challenge the show's young audience, after noting that the same youngsters had been inspired to memorise lyrics to previous songs.<ref name=\"thism_a\">{{cite AV media| title=Interview with Mathew Baynton, Jim Howick and Martha Howe-Douglas| work=[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]| date=12 April 2012 <!-- | accessdate=10 December 2013 No longer available on the programme's website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ShFdlYrw54w-->}}</ref> \"We're History\", styled as a grand finale for the show's final episode, uses stock footage from across the show's run to revisit every major era it ever featured in turn.{{refn|See video clip [http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/videos/5770/ here]|group=note}}\n\n\n==Content and educational value==\nNo formal educational method was applied to the production, and no attempt was made to follow the official [[UK National Curriculum]] for primary school history.<ref name=\"histex_a\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-in-england-history-programmes-of-study | title=National curriculum in England: history programmes of study |work=Official United Kingdom government website | date=11 September 2013 | accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> The show's creators were acutely aware of educational possibilities, but\u2014in line with Deary's overall mandate for the franchise\u2014saw their basic role as popularising history, inspiring further curiosity about the academic subject rather than attempting to teach it seriously.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.timeout.com/london/tv-reviews/yonderland-horribly-ever-after | title=Yonderland: Horribly ever after | work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|date=6 November 2013|accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Tate, Gabriel}}</ref><ref name=\"tbivision_a\">{{cite web | url=http://tbivision.com/highlight/2013/11/kids-tv-seriously/185741/ | title=Kids TV, seriously | work=Television Business International | date=22 November 2013 | accessdate=14 December 2013}}</ref> The show's effectiveness in this respect was endorsed by historical scholars, including presenter [[Dan Snow]].<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> Writing in ''[[The Independent]]'', Gerard Gilbert notes that ''Horrible Histories'' is part of an extensive British [[Black comedy|black-comedy]] tradition not only in adult but also in children's programming.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/horrible-histories-the-best-laughs-are-on-childrens-tv-2194280.html?action=Email |title=Horrible Histories: The best laughs are on children's TV |work=The Independent |date=26 January 2011 |accessdate=31 July 2013|author=Gilbert, Gerard}}</ref> In later series, as usable material from the books began to run out, there was a progression towards more sophisticated, adult sketches in terms of both creativity and educational content, as the show began relying on material that their younger viewers would be less familiar with.<ref name=\"histex_a\"/>\n\n{{quote box|quote=\"My aim for this was always that kids would go away and read up more about a subject. They love all the slapstick, but they also love what Terry does really well in the books\u2014telling you something your parents don\u2019t know. When you\u2019re eight years old you get told what to do by everyone, so being able to teach your dad something is amazing.\"|source=\u2014Caroline Norris, 2013<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\"/>|align=right|width=25em}}\n\nThroughout, emphasis was placed on meshing comedy with the demands of historical accuracy, as defined by the mainstream scholarly consensus on the topic. This stance sometimes encompassed traditionally accepted if not actually well-documented anecdotes, such as those involving [[Caligula]].<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /><ref name=\"histex_a\" /> All the material used on the show was vetted by production assistant and self-described \"tyrannical pedant\" Greg Jenner during both writing and filming; he says that he has counted only eight errors out of more than 4,000 facts presented over the course of the show's run.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /> Costuming and makeup were likewise painstakingly recreated based on primary historical sources where available.<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /><ref name=\"bfi5\"/>\n\nWhen an error was discovered, the effort was made to correct it whenever possible. This process is perhaps most noticeable in the evolution of a song featuring the four [[House of Hanover|Hanoverian]] King Georges: lyrics in the original 2009 video incorrectly saying that [[George I of Great Britain|George I]] had \"died on the [[Close stool|loo]]\" were correctly reassigned to [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] for the song's reprise at the show's 2011 BBC Prom concert.<ref name=\"histex_a\" />\n\nTaking cues from what Deary describes as his \"seriously subversive\" attitude towards the mainstream British history education model<ref name=\"telegraph2_a\" /> meant that the show inevitably incorporated sociopolitical comment. Perhaps most explicitly, Scots-Jamaican nurse [[Mary Seacole]] was deliberately championed in both a sketch and later song as a forgotten heroine in the shadow of [[Florence Nightingale]]. The activities of African-American activists [[Harriet Tubman]] and [[Rosa Parks]] were also showcased, as was ex-slave boxer [[Bill Richmond]].<ref name=\"histex_a\" /> According to Norris, a desire to include more women's stories was hampered by the traditionally male-dominated viewpoint of historical records.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\" /> The show did make an attempt to counteract this by giving showcase songs to the British [[Women's suffrage in the United Kingdom|women's suffrage]] movement and [[Home front during World War II#Mobilisation of women|women's work on the British homefront during World War II]], and wherever possible highlighting strong-willed, dynamic female figures, including [[Queen Victoria]], [[Elizabeth I]] and [[Boudicca]]. Religious controversies, class divisions, the ethics of conquest, and labour conditions were likewise touched on.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" />\n\nThe association with a proven and popular children's brand focusing on potentially sensitive subjects enabled the TV series to deflect any serious controversy regarding the same subjects, as they had demonstrably already been presented to children without any ill effects.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /> Senior writer [[Steve Punt]] said that there were in fact very few complaints regarding the initial series' content, adding that \"everyone was very relieved\".<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /> The producers did consider some topics intrinsically unsuited for an irreverent comic treatment, as for instance the [[Holocaust]] or the harsher details of slavery, and avoided them accordingly.<ref name=\"express_a\" /><ref name=\"histex_a\" /> Norris has described her personal criteria for age suitability as whether she would be nervous watching it with a ten-year-old.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /> While BBC executives in large part were willing to concede the requirements of reflecting historical realities, some topics, notably suicide, needed careful handling to avoid potentially negative impact on younger viewers.<ref name=\"histex_a\" /> The show sometimes acknowledged particularly emotive subject matter (the World War I [[Christmas truce]], for example) by following up the sketch not with a joke, but a more sombre elaboration of the less comedic details.<ref name=\"guardblog_a\"/>\n\n==Production==\nThe TV series used the [[Horrible Histories]] brand, logo and associated trademarks under licence from publisher [[Scholastic Books]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Loveday, Samantha|url=http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/horrible-histories-heading-to-tv/038035|title=Horrible Histories heading to TV|work=Licensing.biz|date=11 October 2007|accessdate=8 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112185858/http://www.licensing.biz/news/read/horrible-histories-heading-to-tv/038035|archive-date=12 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was produced for the BBC by LionTV and Citrus Television,{{refn|[http://citrustelevision.com/ Citrus Television] was formed by several of the ''Horrible Histories'' producers during the show's first series, and is credited alongside LionTV from the second series onward.|group=note}} with post-production being handled by Platform Post Production. Under series producer Norris and directors Brigstocke, Steve Connelly and Chloe Thomas, each series of thirteen episodes took approximately one year to produce. The process included several months of research into the historical facts, two to three months of writing, eight weeks of filming both on location and at London's [[Twickenham Studios]], and three to four months of post-production.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fN5AjcqvPvA | title=Symposium: Horrible Histories: A Masterclass|author1=Norris, Caroline |author2=Farnaby, Simon |author3=Howe-Douglas, Martha | publisher=[[Edinburgh International Television Festival|MediaGuardian Edinburgh Television Festival]] 2012 |medium=YouTube|date=19 September 2012 | accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"express2_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/315797/Horrible-History-s-a-hoot | title=Horrible history's a hoot | work=[[The Daily Express]]| date=22 April 2012 | accessdate=11 December 2013|author=Stephenson, David }}</ref>\n\nAt first the sketches were derived almost exclusively from the books, whose multimedia approach, consisting of short anecdotes interspersed with cartoons, diaries, newspaper articles and recipes, proved easily adaptable to the screen either as raw material or creative inspiration.<ref name=\"guardian_a\" /> In later series, as usable material from the books and other obvious sources began to run out, concepts were drawn from more standard historical texts under Jenner's supervision. He and fellow researchers read through many different studies and picked out suitably quirky, intriguing snippets, which were then pitched to the writers for development.<ref name=\"histex_a\">{{cite web | url=http://d2j7noxmrt3xhh.cloudfront.net/bbchistory/audio/HistoryExtra_2013_05_30.mp3 | title=Podcast: Behind the scenes at Horrible Histories| work=[[BBC History (magazine)|BBC History]] |medium=mp3 podcast file|date=30 May 2013 | accessdate=12 December 2013|author=Hodgman, Charlotte }}</ref>\n\nInspiration for the music videos came from many different sources, and input from all members of the show's creative team was encouraged.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\"/><ref name=\"radiotimes1\"/> With the exception of \"A Gorgeous Georgian Lady\", adapted by Deary from his book ''Gorgeous Georgians'', all songs were original to the series. Once Jenner and Norris had finalised the subject matter and music genre, lyrics were commissioned from the writing team, usually [[Dave Cohen (writer)|Dave Cohen]]. These were rewritten as needed under Norris' supervision to ensure as much factual information as possible was included.<ref name=\"radiotimes1\"/> Webb then composed and recorded each song's instrumental track at Noisegate Studios, hewing as closely as possible to the style of the genre or artist in question. The finished vocal and backing tracks were later returned to Noisegate for post-production by Webb and colleague Matt Katz.<ref name=\"songwriting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/what-s-on/art-of-horrible-songwriting-1-5801893 |title=Art of Horrible songwriting|work=[[Sheffield Telegraph]] |date=28 June 2013 |accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ngmedia\">{{cite web | url=http://www.noisegatemedia.com/portfolio/horrible-histories | title=Noisegate Media Portfolio: Horrible Histories | work=Noisegate Media| accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe 2D animated sequences were directed by Tim Searle of Baby Cow Animation, based on [[Martin Brown (artist)|Martin Brown]]'s illustrations for the books.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.babycow.tv/ | title=Baby Cow Animation: Design & Production | work=Baby Cow Animation | accessdate=27 February 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226215952/http://www.babycow.tv/ | archivedate=26 February 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"youtube_a\">{{cite AV media |title=Horrible Histories behind the scenes: find out how we make the drawings come alive |publisher=CBBC Online|work=Horrible Histories: Behind the Scenes<!--|accessdate=7 February 2014 Part of a video extra series released on the CBBC website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oQFHA_s9yIg -->}}</ref> They were voiced by [[Jon Culshaw]] and [[Jess Robinson]] along with various regular cast members. Video game-styled sketches were achieved using a mix of [[3D computer graphics|3D]] animation and live-action [[green-screen]] footage.<ref>{{cite AV media |title=Horrible Histories behind the scenes: special effects with just a big green sheet|publisher=CBBC Online|work=Horrible Histories: Behind the Scenes<!--|accessdate=27 February 2014 Part of a video extra series released on the CBBC website. YouTube link removed from public view due to copyvio concerns, see here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2MDDvdl1SX8-->}}</ref> Properties frequently were modified foodstuffs, with melted chocolate bars standing in for excrement and soup for vomit.<ref name=\"bfi4\"/>\n\nEach series debuted in the UK in April or May from 2009 to 2013, and on international channels including Canada's [[BBC Kids]], Malaysia's [[NTV7]], The Philippines [[GMA Network]], and Australia's [[ABC3]]. Six special episodes, comprising a mix of new and existing material around a single theme, were broadcast in the UK. \"Horrible Christmas\" (aired in 2010) was followed by a \"Sport Special\" (July 2012, to coincide with the [[2012 London Olympic Games]]) and a \"Scary Special\" (autumn 2012, themed around [[Halloween]]). \"Ridiculous Romance\" (themed around [[Valentine's Day]]) aired in February 2014; the \"Frightful First World War Special\" aired later the same year, as part of the BBC's commemoration of the 100th anniversary of the outbreak of [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories/episodes/2014/1/ | title=2014 Specials \u2013 Horrible Histories | work=British Comedy Guide | date=23 January 2014 | accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BCAspecials\" />\n\nIn autumn 2011, the BBC edited footage from the show's [[Horrible Histories Prom|summer Prom concert]] into an hour-long TV special (\"Horrible Histories' Big Prom Party\"), featuring specially shot linking sketches.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b014b89k | title=CBBC Proms: Horrible Histories' Big Prom Party | work=BBC Proms online guide | accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> In addition, standalone sketches hosted by [[Stephen Fry]], as well as a special \"Bob Hale Report\", were produced as part of the 2012 [[Sport Relief]] benefit programme.<ref name=\"sprelief\">{{cite web | url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/horrible_histories_stephen_fry/episodes/1/7/ | title=Horrible Histories With Stephen Fry: Sport Relief Special | work=British Comedy Guide | date=23 March 2012 | accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/pxgst/horrible-histories--horrible-histories-sport-relief-bob-report | title=Horrible Histories Sport Relief: The Bob Report | work=[[Radio Times]] | date=20 August 2012 | accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> In the same year, several sketches were commissioned as part of the BBC's live television coverage of the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]], to be performed on [[Tower Bridge]], but due to time constraints only one was aired.<ref name=\"djsketches\"/>\n\nThe  producers decided to cease full-time production after the fifth series, citing concerns around the increasing difficulty in finding suitable historical material.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/tv-radio/402593/The-end-of-history-as-we-know-it | title=The end of history as we know it | work=[[The Daily Express|The Sunday Express]]| date=26 May 2013 | accessdate=26 December 2013 | author=Stephenson, David}}</ref> However, the possibility of further specials marking important historical or holiday milestones has been discussed.<ref name=\"BCAspecials\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/000001192/ |title=Horrible Histories to continue with specials|work=British Comedy Guide|date=5 July 2013 |accessdate=31 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the BBC announced that the ''Horrible Histories'' concept would be revived in a new format, focussing on the life and times of a single historical figure per episode. The [[Horrible Histories (2015 TV series)|rebooted series]] was again developed by LionTV and will involve a largely all-new production team and cast, while still retaining Jenner as lead historical consultant and many of the original series's writers. In addition, original stars Farnaby and Howick will return in limited roles.<ref name=\"Series6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/horrible-histories |title=Top comedy stars join CBBC's Horrible Histories|work=BBC Media Centre|date=5 January 2015 |accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\nThe cast members were recruited from sketch and character comedy, having previously had roles in ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'', ''[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]'', ''[[The Thick of It]]'' and ''[[The Mighty Boosh (TV series)|The Mighty Boosh]]'' TV series among others. Several of the writers and researchers also occasionally appeared in front of the camera, including Punt, Jenner, George Sawyer and Susie Donkin, while actors [[Mathew Baynton]] and [[Ben Willbond]] sometimes contributed to the writing. [[Laurence Rickard]] was recruited solely as a writer, but found himself part of both the senior writing staff and starring cast after creating the character of Bob Hale, whose extended, convoluted monologues proved impossible to hand over to anyone else.<ref name=\"bfi4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/live/video/920 |title=Horrible Histories Series Four BFI Q&A |publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=19 June 2013|author=Norris, Caroline with the starring cast}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The starring cast of TV series Horrible Histories arrives at the Children's BAFTAs, 27 November 2011.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The starring cast at the 2011 Children's BAFTAs. L-R: Simon Farnaby, Martha Howe-Douglas, Mathew Baynton, Laurence Rickard, Ben Willbond and Jim Howick]]\n\nIndividual sketches and songs were cast by the production team, sometimes acting on input from the show's stable of performers themselves. While certain roles naturally lent themselves to a particular actor, Norris said that confidence in the entire cast's ability was such that the producers also experimented with casting against type.<ref name=\"bfi4\"/> The demands of filming thirteen episodes' worth of material in the same timeframe as a standard six-episode sketch show, while coping with the many complex makeup and wardrobe changes required, resulted in casting also being partially dependent on the logistics of moving a performer from one character to another.<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /><ref name=\"bfi5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NuxSzQDlaWQ |title=Horrible Histories Series Five BFI Q&A |medium=YouTube|publisher=British Film Institute|date=12 May 2013|accessdate=12 February 2014|author1=Stephenson, David |author2=Norris, Caroline |author3=with the starring cast }}</ref> Recurring characters were if at all possible played by the actor who had originated the part, leading to the development of several signature roles, as for example Baynton's [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], [[Jim Howick]]'s Shouty Man, Rickard's Bob Hale, Willbond's [[Henry VIII]], [[Martha Howe-Douglas]]' [[Elizabeth I]] and [[Simon Farnaby]]'s [[Grim Reaper|Death]].<ref name=\"popm_a\"/><ref name=\"bfi5\"/>\n\nThe performers were allowed to improvise provided that they maintained factual accuracy.<ref name=\"FULLSESSION\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tvchoicemagazine.co.uk/interviewextra/laurence-rickard-horrible-histories | title=Interview with Laurence Rickard| work=[[TV Choice]]| date=24 May 2010 | accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Fowler, Martina}}</ref> Howick said that improvisation was actually often necessary due to the rapid-fire pace of filming, which left very little time to prepare for individual roles.<ref name=\"dog_a\">{{cite web | url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/yonderland/28102/mat-baynton-and-jim-howick-on-yonderland-horrible-histories-more | title=Interview with Mathew Baynton and Jim Howick | work=[[Dennis Publishing|Den of Geek]]| date=8 November 2013| accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Dobbs, Sarah}}</ref> On the other hand, both Rickard and Baynton suggest this enforced spontaneity may have ultimately worked to enhance the comedy, not least by preventing the jokes from becoming over-rehearsed.<ref name=\"express2_a\" />\n\nSix performers (Baynton, Howick, Rickard, Willbond, Howe-Douglas and Farnaby) were credited as main or starring cast throughout the show's run; a seventh, [[Sarah Hadland]], left after the second series but returned with an \"also starring\" credit for the fourth and fifth. The initial sextet appeared from Series 2 onwards as the standard face of the show at premieres and other press opportunities, and performed as a troupe for such peripheral events as the show's BBC Prom concert. They became a particularly close-knit group both personally and professionally.<ref name=\"telegraph_a\" /><ref name=\"DoGinterview\" /> Eventually this led them to continue working together after ''Horrible Histories'' ceased full-time production, creating, writing and starring in the TV series ''[[Yonderland]]'' and feature film comedy ''[[Bill (2015 film)|Bill]]''.<ref name=\"DoGinterview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.denofgeek.com/tv/yonderland/28031/laurence-rickard-and-ben-willbond-on-yonderland-horrible-histories-more | title=Interview with Laurence Rickard and Ben Willbond | work=[[Dennis Publishing|Den of Geek]]| date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=10 December 2013|author=Dobbs, Sarah}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/horrible-histories-launches-to-hit-the-big-screen-with-first-feature-film-untold-story-of-william-bill-shakespeare-to-be-told-8613838.html| title=Horrible Histories to hit the big screen with first feature film: Untold story of William 'Bill' Shakespeare to be told |work=The Independent | date=13 May 2013 | accessdate=4 June 2013|author=Sherwin, Adam}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:6%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Starring Actor\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"width:37%; background:#CEF2E6;\"| Roles (recurring only)\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Mathew Baynton]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Charles II of England]], [[William Shakespeare]], host of \"Historical Fashion Fix\", [[Philip II of Spain]], [[Aristotle]], historical detective D.I. Bones, Nigel the Historical Paramedic, Emperor [[Elagabalus]], [[Guy Fawkes]], [[Menelaus]], [[Richard I of England|Richard I Lionheart]], [[Mark Antony]], [[Emperor Augustus]], [[Bartholomew Roberts|Captain Black Bart]], [[Henry I of England]], [[Charles I of England]], [[James VI and I]] (Series 1 - 4), [[Nicholas II of Russia]], [[George II of Great Britain]], [[Isaac Newton]], [[Charles VII of France]], [[Peter III of Russia]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Simon Farnaby]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Grim Reaper|Death]], [[Caligula]], historical PR agent Cliff Whiteley, [[William the Conqueror]], [[George III of Great Britain]] (Series 1 and 5 and [[BBC Proms|BBC Prom]] concert), [[James II of England]], [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester|Robert Dudley Earl of Leicester]], [[Arthur Phillip]], [[Rameses II]], [[Robert Walpole]], senior Historical Grimefighter, [[Edmond Halley]]\n|- style=\"background:FFFFFF#;\"|\n!scope=\"row\"| [[Martha Howe-Douglas]]\n| <!-- Recurring roles only please, see talkpage for explanation -->[[Elizabeth I of England]], [[Queen Victoria|Victoria of Great Britain]] (Series 2 onward), HHTV 