cued 33 survivors in the next days. Casualties are not known.<ref name=NH044112/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3492.html |title=HMS Tigris |publisher=uboat.net |accessdate=3 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://opus4.kobv.de/opus4-zmsbw/frontdoor/index/index/searchtype/series/id/1/start/57/rows/10/docId/32 |title=Kriegstagebuch der Seekriegsleitung 1939 - 1945. - Teil A ; Band 20. April 1941 |publisher=opus4.kobv.de |accessdate=3 April 2020 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Italian destroyer|Tigre||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Leone|destroyer|2}} was bombed and damaged in the Red Sea {{convert|10|nmi|km}} off Port Sudan by Fleet Air Arm aircraft. She was shelled and sunk by {{HMS|Kingston|F64|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=NH044112/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Urania|1914|2}} \n|flag={{Flag|Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed by aircraft and scuttled in the [[Red Sea]] off [[Dahlak Kebir]], Eritrea ({{coord|40|00.19|N|10|39.52|E}}) to prevent capture by the British. Wreck raised and scrapped in 1949.<ref name=Dive>{{cite book |title=Diving Guide to the Red Sea Wrecks |editor=Andrea Ghiotti |authorlink= |year=1996 |publisher=A A Gaddis & Sons |location=Luxor |isbn= |pages=122\u201339 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5604024|shipname=Urania |accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Westpool||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 26]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|58|12|N|27|40|W}}) by {{GS|U-73|1940|2}} ({{Navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 35 of her 43 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Havelock|H88|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=NH044112/><ref name=Westpool>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/854.html |title=Westpool |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 April 1941 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Adua||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The cargo ship was scuttled at [[Massawa]], [[Italian Eritrea]].<ref name=NH044112/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Arabia|1926|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was scuttled at Massawa.<ref name=NH044112/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Athenic|1937|2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 26]]: The cargo ship straggled behind the convoy. She was torpedoed and damaged in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|58|32|N|20|13|W}}) by {{GS|U-73|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}). All 40 crew were rescued by {{HMS|Arbutus|K86|6}} ({{navy|UK}}) and she sank the next day.<ref name=Athenic>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/859.html |title=Athenic |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=17 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Brenta||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was scuttled at Massawa.<ref name=NH044112/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Buffalo|1916|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Trincola|mooring vessel|2}} struck a mine and sank off [[Singapore]] with the loss of 32 of her 46 crew.<ref name=NH044112/><ref name=Buffalo>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?31607 |title=SS Buffalo (+1941) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/7766.html |title=HMS Buffalo of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Conus||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|56|14|N|31|19|W}}) by {{GS|U-97|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of all 59 crew.<ref name=NH044112/><ref name=Conus>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/862.html |title=Conus |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Crefeld||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was scuttled at Massawa.<ref name=NH044112/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Frauenfels||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was scuttled at Massawa. She was later salvaged by the British, repaired and entered service as ''Empire Niger.<ref name=Ships/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Gerta||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was scuttled at Massawa. She was later salvaged by the British, repaired and entered service as ''Empire Indus.<ref name=Ships/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Italian destroyer|Giovanni Acerbi||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Kingdom of Italy}}\n|desc=World War II: The {{sclass-|Giovanni Sirtori|destroyer|2}} was sunk at Massawa.<ref name=NH044112/><ref name=GA>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?138311 |title=RM Giovanni Acerbi (+1941) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Harbledown||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy SC 26]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|58|24|N|23|20|W}}) by {{GS|U-94|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 16 of her 41 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Veteran|D72|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=NH044112/><ref name=Harbledown>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/860.html |title=Harbledown |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Imperio||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was scuttled at Massawa. She was later salvaged.<ref name=NH044112/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck