] off [[Milford Haven]], [[Pembrokeshire]] with the loss of all hands.<ref name=NH044122/><ref name=Caroline>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?71778 |title=HMT Caroline (1941) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=18 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=JC>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?10985 |title=SS Johanna Caroline (+1941) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=22 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|LCT 5|LCT5|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[LCT Mk 1 class|''Mk 1''-class]] [[Landing Craft, Tank]] was bombed, beached and abandoned at [[Monemvassia]] [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/17583.html |title=HMS LCT 5 (LCT 5)of the Royal Navy |publisher=U Boat.net |accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Moncousu||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The depot ship was bombed and sunk at [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]] by Luftwaffe aircraft.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Oilfield||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 121]]: The tanker was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|60|05|N|17|00|W}}) by {{GS|U-96|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 47 of her 55 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{HMT|St Zeno|FY280|6}} ({{navy|UK}})<ref name=NH044122/><ref name=Oilfield>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/889.html |title=Oilfield |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Port Hardy||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy HX 121]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|60|14|N|15|20|W}}) by {{GS|U-96|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of one of her 98 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Zaafara||2}} ({{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=PH>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/890.html |title=Port Hardy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|U-65|1940|2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[German Type IX submarine|Type IXB]] [[submarine]] was depth charged and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|60|04|N|15|45|W}}) by {{HMS|Douglas}} ({{navy|UK}}) with the loss of all 46 crew. }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==29 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=29 April 1941 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Aetos|1910|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Greece}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The coaster was bombed and sunk in Greek waters by [[Luftwaffe]] aircraft.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Ambrose Fleming||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: [[Convoy EC 13]]: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the [[North Sea]] ({{coord|53|14|N|1|08|E}}) by {{ship|German torpedo boat|S-29||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 11 crew.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''C 293'' \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The C lighter was bombed and sunk at Plymouth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-history.net/xDKWW2-4104-31APR02.htm |title=Naval Events, April 1941, Part 2 of 2, Tuesday 15tt \u2013 Wednesday 30th |publisher=Naval History |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Chakla}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The armed boarding vessel was bombed and sunk at [[Tobruk]], [[Italian Libya|Libya]] by [[Junkers Ju 87]] aircraft of III ''Staffeln'', [[Sturzkampfgeschwader 1]] and II ''Staffeln'', [[Sturzkampfgeschwader 2]], Luftwaffe and 96 & 236 Squadrons, [[Regia Aeronautica]].<ref name=seekrieg194104/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.awm.gov.au/collection/127950/ |publisher=awm.gov.au|title=Australian War Memorial |accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Chiloe||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Chile}}\n|desc=The passenger ship ran aground on [[Puchoco Point]] and was wrecked.<ref name=Chiloe>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?37180 |title=SS Chiloe (+1941) |publisher=Wrecksite |accessdate=21 December 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|City of Nagpur||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The passenger ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean ({{coord|52|30|N|26|00|W}}) by {{GS|U-75|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 16 lives. Survivors were rescued by {{HMS|Hurricane|H06|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Elsi|1891|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Greece}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in [[Suda Bay]] by Luftwaffe aircraft. She was later salvaged and repaired by the Germans.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Kalua||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in the North Sea off the mouth of the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] by [[Junkers Ju 88]] aircraft of I ''Staffeln'', [[K\u00fcstenfliegergruppe 506]], Luftwaffe. All crew were rescued.<ref name=seekrieg194104/><ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Konistra|1907|2}} \n|flag={{flag|Greece}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was bombed and sunk in Suda Bay by Luftwaffe aircraft. She was later salvaged and repaired by the Germans.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''HMML 278'' \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[Fairmile B motor launch]] struck a mine and sank at [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]] with the loss of all hands.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Pessac}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The auxiliary patrol vessel was bombed and sunk at [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]] by Luftwaffe aircraft. She was raised, repaired and returned to service in 1942.<ref name=NH044122/> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==30 April==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 April 1941 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German  patrol boat|CF 1||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The ''CF 1''-class river motor patrol boat was lost on this date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navypedia.org/ships/germany/ger_mb_cf1.htm |title=CF 1 class River Motor Patrol Boat, Germany |publisher=Navypedia |accessdate=14 April 2016}}</ref>}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Fermoy|J40|6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass2-|Hunt|minesweeper|2||1916}} was bombed and damaged at [[Malta]] by [[Luftwaffe]] aircraft and declared a constructive total loss. She was further damaged by bombing on 4 May and sank.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{MV|Lassell||2}} \n|flag={{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n|desc=World War II: The cargo ship was torpedoed and sunk in the Atlantic Ocean {{convert|250|nmi|km}} south west of the [[Cape Verde Islands]], Portugal ({{coord|12|55|N|28|56|W}}) by {{GS|U-107|1940|2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of two of her 53 crew. Survivors were rescued by {{SS|Benvrackie|1922|2}} and {{SS|Egba||2}} (both {{flag|United Kingdom|civil}}).<ref name=NH044122/><ref name=Lassell>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/893.html |title=Lassell |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMIS|Parvati}} \n|flag={{navy|British India}}\n|desc=World War II: The patrol vessel struck a mine and sank in the [[Red Sea]] ({{coord|13|11|N|42|54|E}}) with the loss of 16 of her 37 crew. Survivors were rescued by a Royal Navy ship.<ref name=NH044122/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Peuplier}} \n|flag={{navy|United Kingdom}}\n|desc=World War II: The tug was bombed and sunk off Plymouth.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/7589.html |title=HMS Peoplier of the Royal Navy |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMT|Trusty Star||6}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=World War II: The 